To estimate how well these ten stocks represent the ETF IHF, we can use their current % of assets, normalized to 100%, to calculate the contributions of each stock to a portfolio's Beta and Return if the portfolio was made of these 10 stocks in the proportion the ETF holds. The calculations of Beta and return are shown below:

From the chart, it's clear that a portfolio of just the top 10 holdings could offer a 6.11% higher return and a 0.12 lower Beta than the ETF. However, these two portfolios might not be statistically different from each other.

To determine if these portfolios are statistically different, we'll calculate the standard deviation of each of the top 10 stocks and normalize it to 100% to compare their accumulated standard deviation to that of the ETF IHF.

Dream-land is one of Edgar Allan Poe's self-proclaimed better poems. In “Dream-Land,” he uses the term “Thulé” in lines 6 and 56, which Mabbott traces back to Virgil. Virgil used the term to refer to an island north of Britain, considered the edge of the known world by the Greeks. While Virgil certainly used the term, there's a more current source to which some credit must be given. Poe was particularly fascinated by German authors. Karl J. Arndt, in his book Poe’s Politian and Goethe’s Mignon, points out the similarity between Poe’s and Goethe’s poems, concluding that Poe was indeed imitating Goethe.

The Oxford Companion to English Literature notes that Goethe was a renowned writer of the poetic drama Faust, published in two parts, with the first appearing in 1808 and the second in the year of Goethe's death, 1832. Within the second part of Faust, there's a short poem titled “The King of Thulé.” This poem tells of a king whose wife dies after giving him a goblet. He then begins to drink heavily and mourn his loss, ultimately deciding to end his life by throwing the goblet into the ocean. The description of this king and the atmosphere in “Dream-Land” are very similar, perhaps reflective of Poe’s own struggles with loss and alcohol. Faust was also adapted into a romantic drama by H P Grattan in 1842, just a year before Poe used the term Thule in “The Pit and the Pendulum.”

Poe references Thule twice in his collected writings. He uses the phrase “ultma Thule” in “The Pit and the Pendulum,” and in “Dream-Land,” he uses the term twice to frame the poem. “The King of Thulé” and “Dream-Land” can be seen as companion pieces. In “Dream-Land,” the speaker describes the bleak landscape of Thule, filled with the ghostly memories of dead friends and a world devoid of color. This description resonates with the themes in “The King of Thulé,” where the king has lost his will to live and is haunted by his wife's memory. The poem reads as if the speaker has stepped into Goethe’s work.

Goethe was a significant author that Poe would have known, if for no other reason than his respect for Tennyson. When asked if he admired Tennyson, Poe did mention his appreciation for Tennyson, but he would also have been exposed to Goethe’s work through various reproductions that became popular after the original publication.

In California, a customer injured after slipping and falling on an applesauce spill in a grocery store might be awarded punitive damages if the store manager's actions showed malice. The manager knew of the spill twice but didn't clean it for a half-hour because he was eating dinner. The manager's actions could be seen as willful and conscious disregard for probable harm, even if not intending to cause harm. A judge is unlikely to dismiss Jennifer Palmer's punitive damage claim if she can present evidence that the store manager's actions were malicious.

Four years ago, I attended a course on Islam at CBC. One of the main topics that sparked heated debate was whether Islam is a hostile religion. This question is even more pertinent today. Reflecting on the events since 9/11, I've noticed a shift in mass media's portrayal of Islam and extremists, from hostility to extreme tolerance. In 2001, a presidential candidate with the name Barack Obama, who has a Muslim background in his family, was unimaginable.

The life of the Prophet Muhammad, as recounted in his biography, is intriguing. The narrative paints Muhammad as a sort of martyr, misunderstood and humble, rather than someone who forcibly converted tribes. According to the biography, one by one, people came to see the 'truth' in his teachings and sought him out. This style of portrayal is reminiscent of Jesus' ministry, particularly the miracle of multiplying food—mutton and milk—to feed forty men. This approach seems to downplay the life and miracles of Jesus.

Moreover, many stories in the biography aim to provide 'proof' of conversions to Islam, often presented as third-party accounts. While this might seem to validate the stories, it also makes them appear more questionable. What bothers me most is the attempt to elevate Muhammad to a godly figure, portraying him as humble, wise, and gentle. However, historical accounts contradict this image, and I can't help but wonder if Muslims today are aware of the true history behind Muhammad's rise to power.

The teachings of Jesus and the beliefs he held during his lifetime were swiftly abandoned in the evolution of Christian thought that followed his life. A historical trend shows Christianity drifting further away from its origin over time. Today's world displays increasing awareness and unprecedented progressive tendencies. While some people cling to traditional beliefs and resist any thinking beyond what they were taught, this group's influence may not be significant enough to shape the whole. Among Christians, a growing historical awareness will intensify in future years. There will be a growing desire to distinguish between the doctrines added to Christianity over time and the original intent of the religion's founder. It may take decades or even centuries, but the outcome is inevitable: a reversal in the trend of Christian history. This will involve a progression back to its original form, with a movement gaining strength that peels away layers of doctrine, one by one, as if turning back the clock. This reversal will lead to a clearer understanding of Jesus' teachings, before any other ideas were introduced. When this trend sweeps through the United States and Europe, influencing millions to worship as if living in Jesus' time, the church will remain strong to guide the way. However, with the theological clock turned back, the extreme diversity in Christendom will reduce to more uniformity. Between regions, denominations, and divisions of every kind, differences will give way to increasing similarities. Human history is filled with great reversals. Just consider how Christians were once persecuted, shunned, and killed by the Roman Empire, but later, the empire became a Christian institution. Our country has evolved from African-American slavery to African-American leadership. The great reversal coming in our future will play out in the realm of the Christian religion, undoing history to seek the source and reducing diversity in the process. It is important to note that part of what will make this process possible is reading Jesus' words metaphorically, rather than literally. So, what has changed since Jesus' lifetime?

If we look far back into history, we find only Judaism, the theological foundation for Christianity. Monotheism, the perception of a divinely revealed religion, and the authority of the Hebrew scriptures were already present by the time Rome took control of Jerusalem in 63 B.C.E. The Jewish population was not united; they divided into Sadducees, Pharisees, Essenes, Zealots, and a majority of ordinary people.

In my view, The Jungle vividly demonstrates humanity's inherent greed and self-interest. Individuals only focus on enhancing their own lives and ignore others, especially those less fortunate. Sinclair's narrative emphasizes this theme through the owners and managers of the colossal factories. These figures are singularly driven by the desire to expand and prosper their businesses, indifferent to the harm caused by their operations. "The line of the buildings stood clear-cut and black against the sky; here and there out of the mass rose the great chimneys, with the river of smoke streaming away to the end of the world" paints a stark picture of the pollution and damage inflicted by these factories. The owners carelessly disregard the plight of workers and the ecosystem, exemplified by the choking smoke and waste from the pens. They prioritize profit above all, even exploiting their employees' labor. "So from the top to bottom the place is simply a seething cauldron of jealousies and hatreds; there is no loyalty or decency anywhere about it, there is no place in it where a man counted for anything against a dollar," Sinclair writes, highlighting the harsh working conditions and lack of worker's safety regulations. This environment resulted in employees being treated as disposable, with no support or help even in death. Unions, meant to protect workers, often profited off these very individuals, exacerbating their suffering. Employees were trapped in a system where they were essentially slaves, forced to endure deplorable conditions both inside and outside the factories.

Many authors employ various methods to evoke specific feelings or attitudes in their readers towards significant topics. One such technique is the pairing of adjectives with nouns in an unconventional manner. Another method is the symbolism of objects, where a symbol is given a particular meaning and then utilized for the same purpose. F. Scott Fitzgerald uses these techniques extensively in his novel "The Great Gatsby." For instance, he often associates colors like yellow, green, white/gray, and red/pink with certain emotions or themes. In "The Great Gatsby," Fitzgerald builds up a symbolic meaning for white/gray and later uses this meaning to convey a sense of uniformity or insignificance around particular subjects.

Fitzgerald establishes the meaning of white/gray in the novel's beginning, where he frequently uses both colors. Characters like Daisy and Jordan are often "in white" (8), and even Nick wears "white flannels" (41) to Gatsby's party. The only instances where characters are not wearing white are during Nick's descriptions of Gatsby's party, where "the halls... are gaudy with primary colors" (40). Fitzgerald also employs white/gray to symbolize uniformity in people and places. For example, as Nick goes to work, he travels "down the white chasms of lower New York" (56), and the names of partygoers are "gray names" (61) on his timetable. Moreover, the novel describes simple or unimportant characters and places in terms of white/gray; Jordan and Daisy share a "white girlhood" (19), there are "gray cars" and "gray land" (23) in the valley of ashes, and an "Italian child" is described as "gray" (26) while a dog-seller is a "gray old man" (27).

After imbuing white/gray with a specific meaning, Fitzgerald uses these colors to represent uniformity or insignificance. This technique starts with Daisy, who is first depicted in a "white" dress in a "little white roadster." After a period without significant use of white or gray, Daisy's role becomes more uniform, like something Gatsby wants but cannot possess. Fitzgerald continues this pattern with Daisy wearing a "white" dress (115) and having a "gray haze of Daisy’s fur collar" (18) to emphasize her status as a uniform addition rather than a unique character.

San Diego County is a hotbed of agricultural activity, thanks to its mild, sunny climate. Crops grown here include tomatoes, citrus fruits, leafy greens, squash, broccoli, herbs, tree fruits like peaches and lemons, berries, honey, and peppers. There's a thriving market for organic community-supported agriculture, with many local organizations boasting lengthy waiting lists. Organic eggs and milk are also in high demand. Many organic farms offer tours and recreational activities like hiking and birdwatching. This type of operation allows farmers to benefit from government programs while enhancing habitat and offering educational experiences. However, organic farming can be more labor-intensive and costly due to the lack of chemical pesticides and fertilizers, and it may have higher pest and weed management costs. It often requires more labor and management to maintain soil health and biodiversity. Additionally, non-farming tasks such as planting cover crops, strategic grazing, and invasive species removal can also incur significant labor costs. This makes it a good idea for the landowner to seek financial aid or expertise to balance profits and habitat quality.

The selected land is a 160-acre parcel adjacent to the town of Potrero in unincorporated San Diego County, California. It's a mix of chaparral, nonnative Mediterranean grassland, and oak woodland near the Cleveland National Forest. This region is part of the East County Southern Foothills ecoregion of the San Diego Multiple Species Conservation Plan. The plan identifies over a hundred species of plants and animals, many of which are endangered or declining, such as the Stephens' kangaroo rat, mountain yellow-legged frog, various butterfly species, and the California gnatcatcher, while burrowing owls are also at risk. The land was inhabited by Native Americans for centuries and later used by cattle ranchers and cordwood sellers in the late 1800s. This parcel was part of an original homestead, likely used for grazing and/or wood production.

Culture shapes every negotiation, and it's not just about what it is, but also what it's not. It's not uniform, it's not singular, and it's not something you can judge or change. Saying "all Russians are stubborn" or "all Japanese are accommodating" is oversimplifying. Understanding culture's impact on negotiations is crucial. When exploring a foreign culture, we relate it to our own, and comparisons naturally arise. To understand a culture, study its history, prejudices, and values. Accept it, work within its boundaries, especially if you're at a disadvantage. Respecting traditions and beliefs helps overcome cultural barriers. Culture isn't just national; companies have their own culture too. In a negotiation, knowing your opponent's personal values can make all the difference. If saving face is valued, you won't publicly shame them. If a hard bargain is valued, don't rush to settle. Understanding these generalities before the table is crucial, but knowing your opponent personally can make the negotiation more effective.

“The fool hath said in his heart, ‘There is no God.’” This statement first appears in Psalm 14 of the Christian Bible and serves as the starting point for St. Anselm’s argument for the existence of God. Similarly, Thomas Aquinas also holds this belief. Given that both are arguing for the same idea, and our task is to determine which argument is stronger, we must assume, for the sake of simplicity, that both are correct in their belief in the God of the Bible. To compare their arguments effectively, we must focus on a God that matches the one they describe. Neither St. Anselm nor St. Thomas Aquinas offers a complete justification for belief in God.
	To demonstrate this, let’s first look at St. Anselm’s basic argument. Anselm’s approach involves gaining understanding through faith, suggesting that the proof for God lies within one’s own mind. He argues that since we can conceive of God’s existence, we cannot deny it. While his reasoning can be convoluted, the core of it is that the proof of God is found within our own understanding. This is a concept known as faith within Christian texts, where one accepts the existence of God without needing irrefutable empirical evidence.
	St. Thomas Aquinas, on the other hand, posits that the existence of God can be proven through reason and empirical evidence, without relying on faith. This approach could be advantageous for evangelism, as it allows new converts to be persuaded by logic alone. Aquinas presents five logical arguments supporting the existence of God: change, causation, contingency, degrees of excellence, and harmony. Each argument essentially shows that the proof of God lies in the logical necessity for his existence. For example, if you have a puzzle but one piece is missing, you can infer its features and existence based on the rest of the puzzle, even without seeing it.

Long ago, in the fifth or sixth century BCE, a future Buddha was born. Throughout his life, he left the world behind and achieved enlightenment, laying the foundation for Buddhism, with Theravada Buddhism being the most traditional sect. The faith has existed for around twenty-five hundred years, evolving significantly since Buddha's time. For example, in Sri Lanka, the annual water-cutting ceremony involves monks and laypeople, though Buddha never taught about such festivities. The Theravada Buddhist community has altered its core principles, influenced by both external and internal factors, both friendly and unfriendly. Let's delve into what makes Theravada Buddhism tick. Buddhists find solace in the triple gem: the Buddha, the Dhamma, and the Sangha. The Dhamma includes the Tripitaka, the three baskets, which contain Suttas, disciplinary rules, and metaphysical components. Key notions include Anatta (no soul), Dukkha (inherent suffering), and Anicca (impermanence). Understanding these concepts can help break the cycle of death and rebirth, known as Sansara, and eliminate lobha (desire), dosa (hatred), and moha (delusion). The Vinaya Pitaka outlines rules for life, with five precepts for laypeople and many more for monks. The core doctrine revolves around the four noble truths: first, life is suffering; second, attachment causes suffering; third, suffering can be overcome.

Once upon a time, the United States and Mexico were locked in a long-lasting rivalry that lasted from 1836 to 1893. The height of their animosity was the Mexican-American War of 1846-1848, where the U.S. triumphed over Mexico, securing Texas and the American Southwest. Other skirmishes occurred between them before the First World War. Their rivalry stemmed from disagreements on religion, culture, and tradition, as well as clashing material interests. This is not unusual for neighboring nations, as David M. Pletcher (1977) noted, “Only in Mexico and Cuba can one find long-lasting overarching American diplomatic problems” (p. 41). Both countries were geographically close to the U.S. and held rival positions, unlike many other Latin American nations that enjoyed good relations with the U.S. Religious differences, a remnant of colonial times, played a significant role in their enmity.

Sally Frahm (2001) highlighted that "if in the twentieth century Americans were opposed to fascism and communism, in the eighteenth and nineteenth they were opposed to Catholicism and monarchy" (p.86). Thus, the ideological struggle between the U.S. and Mexico was more about religion than politics, much like the Cold War between the U.S. and the Soviet Union. The distrust between them was passed down from their colonial rulers, the English and Spanish, blocking amiable foreign relations.

Diehl and Goerts (2000) documented 17 disputes between Mexico and the U.S. during their 57-year rivalry, most of which were territorial issues. Border raids and outlaw activities from American towns were major problems until both nations took military action on their borders (Schmitt 1974 p. 97). The rivalry began to ease when Mexico became reliant on the U.S., and finally ended as American ambitions shifted from territorial expansion to economic intervention in Mexico in the late 19th century (Schmitt 1974 p. 109, 110).

Fifteen years ago, I was struck down unexpectedly by a hidden illness. I was a nurse at the time, having chosen nursing to ensure a secure future, as I'd grown up without it. "You'll always find work, people will always get sick" was my mantra. Despite my dream to be a mix of scientist and journalist, I chose nursing.

Now, at 46, single, and unable to work, I'm still disabled. Living on Social Security Disability for 15 years has left me with nothing to call my own. Every day is a struggle, an assault on my security, safety, and self-esteem. Nothing is certain anymore, but I know I couldn't have survived without my family and friends.

Life is full of emergencies, big and small. No matter how well we prepare, some things are too big to overcome alone. I agree that we shouldn't rely solely on big government, but we should learn to trust each other, to help and ask for help, rather than isolate ourselves.

Conservatives talk about the "rugged individualism" that built the country, but our forefathers crossed the Rockies in wagon trains, not alone. They collaborated, respected each other, and shared resources.

So, be prepared. I have a disaster kit with first aid supplies, water purifying tablets, plastic sheeting, duct tape, flashlights, batteries, candles, matches, and canned goods. If you have the land and resources for a farm, can or preserve your food. But also, get to know your neighbors.

How and why do organisms evolve the way they do? Are there any rules or limitations that guide the direction of their evolutionary changes? In 1917, D’Arcy Thompson noted that even then, “the zoologist has scarcely begun to dream of defining in mathematical language the simplest organic forms.” Even today, mathematical modeling is being applied to various aspects of mollusk skeletogenesis, both in their development and through evolutionary history (e.g., Raup and Stanley, 1981). Our research aims to understand how mathematical modeling of ontogenetic and phylogenetic changes in Prunum, combined with experimental studies, can help us grasp the mechanisms behind the direction and magnitude of evolutionary-developmental changes. We used X-radiographic images of Prunum species to identify quantitative parameters that can be used to model hypothetical and actual skeletal morphologies. These parameters were input into the software program CerioShell (Stone, 1995). We modeled hypothetical shell morphologies to interpret the limits of possible morphological changes in Prunum, with these results being combined with experimental and descriptive studies to better understand macroevolutionary events in this group.

Think of a shell as a tube that winds through 360 degrees of space. These turns or loops are called whorls, spiraling around an imaginary central axis called the columella. The speed at which these whorls grow varies, and a continuous line separates each one, known as a suture. The largest whorl, the body whorl, is usually the last. The spire consists of all the whorls except the last, with the apex being the tip of the spire and the opposite end being the base. The animal exits the shell through an opening called the aperture.

Shells can be viewed from several angles: apical, basal, apertural, and abapertural. The usual orientation is an apertural view, with the aperture facing the viewer and the apex pointing up.

To count whorls, first view the shell from the apical view, then find the line where the first suture begins. Count the whorls from this line, estimating to a quarter of a whorl if necessary.

A shell can be seen as a series of apertures traveling through time and space as the animal builds its shell. The path of the aperture can be traced using coordinates of each whorl’s aperture, as well as horizontal and vertical radii.

This trajectory can be represented graphically and mathematically. Once a mathematical formula is established, it becomes possible to modify the parameters and alter the mollusk’s skeletogenesis.

Indonesia's rates of neonatal and infant mortality have been stagnant over the past decade, despite it being on track to meet many Millennium Development Goals, such as water and sanitation targets. However, progress in child and maternal health has been dismally slow, falling short of 2015 goals. The root causes of these issues are multifaceted and suggest a need to bolster the overall health system rather than rely solely on targeted interventions.

Indonesia has made strides in the number of births attended by skilled health workers, with 72% now meeting this standard. However, the category includes traditional workers like midwives who cannot handle complicated pregnancies, leading to high maternal death rates due to hemorrhage. The improvements in this indicator are deceiving, and significant work remains. Additionally, there's been a decrease in the percentage of diarrheal cases in children under five treated by health professionals, and data on postnatal care is incomplete, indicating low rates nationwide.

Cesarean-section rates remain below expectations at 4%, and the rates vary considerably between urban (7%) and rural (2%) areas, highlighting inequities in healthcare access. A 27% gap in service utilization between the poorest and richest quintiles underscores the challenge of accessing healthcare for the poor, likely due to out-of-pocket costs.

When considering how to improve neonatal and maternal care, the key question is whether Indonesia should focus on program-specific approaches or strengthen the entire health system without singling out pre- and postnatal care. While programmatic approaches are enticing for their targeted and manageable objectives and faster results, they may divert funding and resources away from other areas and lead to uncoordinated duplication of services. For example, heavy investment in HIV/AIDS programming can negatively impact other sectors like family planning.

Victorian literature is known for its meticulous attention to detail and its focus on the aristocracy of the era. Two notable exceptions to this tradition are Oliver Twist and Wuthering Heights. Both works incorporate elements of mystery and the unusual, which are not typically seen in Victorian novels. This adds depth to the characters and their motivations, providing insight into their inner selves and emotions.

In Oliver Twist, these mysterious occurrences often reveal Oliver's inner turmoil and his awareness of the true nature of his surroundings. For instance, during the shooting sequence in chapter 28, Oliver relives the event in a dreamlike state. This passage highlights Oliver's lack of control over the events unfolding and his dire physical condition, as indicated by his hallucinations of Sikes and Crackit. The shooting itself is so overwhelming that it numbs all his senses, and he does not notice the “unseen hand” that bears him away. He experiences his despair over again, removed from the initial shock of pain, now constant and linked with fear. This reinforces the idea that Oliver has little control over his circumstances. Additionally, it suggests a growing sense of defeat in Oliver, as if old Fagin's influence is breaking him, making him accept this despair and affecting his ability to react.

A few years back, I was working at an after-school program, helping elementary-aged students with their homework. While I did my best to aid them in all subjects, my true strength lay in English and reading. I was summoned by one of the instructors to lend a hand to a young boy named Adrian, who was having trouble reading. It became apparent that something was amiss; Adrian had peculiar issues, correctly pronouncing some letters while struggling with others. Intrigued by this, I tried to help, but our progress was slow. Things took a turn when Adrian's mother walked in. She spoke only Spanish, and my limited knowledge made communication a challenge. However, a revelation struck me: Adrian could read, but he struggled with the English alphabet. I hope Adrian has improved since then.

I share this story to highlight the complexities of the language barrier in schools, particularly in California. It's not always as clear-cut as it seems, even for children who speak perfect English. Reading can be a significant hurdle. The solution for Adrian was straightforward: tutoring in English reading, focusing on the alphabet and pronunciations. Yet, for children who barely speak English, the solution is far more intricate. There isn't a one-size-fits-all answer. Dual language systems, mainstream immersion, private tutors, ESL classes—none alone can solve this issue. The key is to combine all these methods.

Firstly, the dual language system is a brilliant concept, beneficial for children whose first language is Spanish, but also for all children. Research shows that children in these programs outperform their peers academically. Many fear that this system is a waste of resources or that it only benefits a few. This is incorrect. If implemented widely, all children would benefit. So, how can we achieve this? Requiring all teachers to be bilingual is unrealistic. Instead, special aides or tutors who are bilingual could be employed.

From the time we're kids, most of us are told there's something out there bigger than ourselves, bigger than our understanding. Some of us head to church or temple, while others look inward for answers. Many embrace the beliefs passed down, but some reject them outright, believing their personal reality is all there is. We may switch our values, searching for a sense of self through our unique spiritual paths. We yearn for a beacon in the dark to guide us out into the light.

“A cardinal,” my dad said when I asked about his favorite bird. We sat on the porch, rain pounding on the tin roof as we smoked. The gutters drained the downpour, drowning the plants at the edge. He stared out, half-searching, half-remembering, thinner and sparser than before. I felt alone, afraid, unable to discuss the pain of losing him. I hugged him, sat closer, and gazed into the June twilight with him.

Dad passed in December, five days after my birthday. Chemo and radiation prolonged his suffering. Why would a God do that? I thought in the night. I said no prayers. If a God existed, I believed he'd stopped listening long ago.

I couldn't watch Dad leave, so I stayed away. I wanted to remember him by how he lived, not how he died. I curled up in bed for three days, waiting for news.

No one called me.

The classic "Gothic Novel," as described by Ian Watt in The Rise of the Gothic Novel, is essentially an "oxymoron" combining "Old-New," utilizing elements of both "ancient" and "modern" romances. The Gothic genre has been both lambasted and celebrated—accused of lacking depth and praised for its 'terrible sublime' allure. The first "Gothic Novel," Horace Walpole's The Castle of Otranto, merged "old" theatrical elements and 'new' naturalistic mimicry into a 'modern' novel format. Walpole's work is marked by a blend of medieval Gothic theatre, architecture, and traditions, with the term 'gothic' then describing various peoples, styles, and periods, often seen as archaic or unsophisticated. The fusion of the theatrical 'Gothic' and the novel's personal character psychology allows the genre to persist, remaining both obsolete and fresh to distant readers. One core Gothic theme is Chivalry, a medieval idea of knightly training, which the original Gothic novel, The Castle of Otranto, retained and transformed. Chivalry is significant to Gothic writers as it represents the ideal knight, embodying courage, honor, and competence, qualities perceived as lacking in contemporary society. Walpole, writing in a politically turbulent era, perhaps subtly questioned society's loss of medieval moral and innate goodness, evident in characters like Frederic. The reader encounters Frederic, described with many chivalric traits: he is a prince, has endured tragedy, and is presumed dead at the hands of infidels, exemplifying the 'gallant and courteous Knight' trope, with exaggeration hinting at the future evolution of Gothic to Romanticism (66).

Supply chain management is the continuum of processes that move products from the point of customer order through raw material stages, production, distribution, and finally reaching customers. This concept was coined in 1982 by Keith Oliver, a consultant. Keith Oliver described the entire cycle of planning, executing, and managing the supply chain to meet customers' needs quickly and efficiently. The supply chain is composed of six essential components: production, supply, inventory, location, transportation, and information. Managers utilize these elements to deliver excellent customer service.

The first step in the supply chain process is production, which is pivotal to the entire operation. Production establishes the foundation by determining the who, what, when, where, and how of the production process. Managers must understand customer demands, which can be gauged through market analysis. By assessing the market, management can determine what products should be produced and in what quantities. Once product requirements are set, managers decide where to produce the goods and select the most suitable plant for volume and quality, considering customer needs. After setting the production location, managers focus on scheduling workloads and maintaining equipment. Production is crucial, and every detail must be meticulously planned to avoid costly delays or inefficiencies.

The second key element is supply. Supply involves strategic decisions to define a facility's core capabilities and form outsourcing partnerships. A company may have multiple production divisions for a single product, each with distinct equipment, workers, and specializations. Managers must choose the best-fitting division for each production step. Outsourcing to other companies can enhance speed, quality, and flexibility while keeping costs low.

Hitler is alive in Burma, according to the sign. Ellen Page, the actress from Juno, stands alone on a street corner, holding a cardboard sign with the message written in Sharpie. Burma, also known as Myanmar, is a Southeastern Asian country under a tyrannical military junta that took power in 1962 through a coup d’état. In 2007, a series of street protests, led by monks, began, earning the name “The Saffron Revolution” due to the color of the robes they wore. Initially, the Burmese government tolerated peaceful gatherings, but as the protests grew, the military responded with violence, invading and destroying monasteries around the country. Foreign journalists were rounded up and imprisoned on-site, with one Japanese photojournalist, Kenji Nagai, killed for being at a protest. The official death toll is 13, but Colonel Hla Win, a defector from the army, claimed thousands more were killed.

This is not new. Throughout history, governments have suppressed dissent and maintained complete control over their citizens. Early Roman emperors claimed divine right to rule, Japanese emperors are believed to be gods leading their people to prosperity through Motorola phones and hara-kiri, and even our current president, George W. Bush, has weekly meetings with Ted Haggard, leader of Stupid People Worldwide, a subsidiary of the Republican Party.

Some of the most notable examples include the 1989 protests at Tiananmen Square, where students and activists were killed, with death tolls ranging from 200 to 3,000. In the 1990s, the Rwandan genocide saw Hutu militia groups, aided by the government, systematically kill Tutsis and political moderates. Hitler's Third Reich was a period where Jews were rounded up and killed across several countries.

Duke Ellington left an indelible mark on jazz music, primarily due to his sustained career and his ability to mold his orchestra into a harmonious and inventive entity. His subtle presence on the piano frequently goes unnoticed, but as a composer, Ellington was exceptional at crafting intricate pieces that highlighted the unique talents of his band members. He masterfully created a framework where soloists could freely improvise, while also writing tightly orchestrated parts that emphasized the distinctive styles of his musicians. By doing so, he accentuated the overall tone of the orchestra, producing fresh and original sounds tailored to each piece. Ellington's skill in capturing the individual musicians' sounds and how they blended together in a growing ensemble resulted in some of jazz's most groundbreaking compositions.

The Grove Music dictionary lauds Ellington's innovative style, citing Creole Love Call as an early instance where he utilized voice as a jazz instrument. This piece, a slow and deliberate twelve-bar blues, showcases Ellington’s ability to complement his soloists’ styles and add texture and color without lyrics. The composition is structured as follows:

- Chorus 1: A call and response between the voice and reeds, starting smoothly and melodic before transitioning to a rougher sound.
- Chorus 2: Muted trumpet solo that embellishes the basic melody and highlights extended blue notes.
- Chorus 3: Sweeping clarinet solo in a high register, supported by a subtle syncopated piano phrase.
- Chorus 4: The full band echoes the first chorus with a call and response between brass and reeds.
- Chorus 5: The peak of the piece, with reeds taking the lead in a high register, backed by syncopated stop time from brass and rhythm sections.
- Chorus 6: A return to the structure of the first chorus, with the voice adopting the "growl" technique as an instrument.
- Tag: A brief tag featuring a vocal run and a dissonant trombone finish.

Ellington’s use of voice as a tone color here is just one of many stylistic traits that run throughout his work.

In "Hot and Bothered", recorded the following year, Ellington integrates his knack for tight orchestration with his ear for tone color. A call and response sequence between Bubber Miley on muted trumpet and Baby Cox’s scat singing demonstrates this, creating a rich and complementary sound by blending vocal elements of Miley’s playing with instrumental aspects of Cox’s voice. In "It Don’t Mean a Thing (If It Ain’t Got That Swing)", Ellington employs Joe "Tricky Sam" Nanton, a long-time member of his orchestra, to great effect, using his muted trombone to introduce the melody.

She's always felt a void, an unfulfilled longing. This desire began when she was 14, embracing teenage life, and it's still there at 17. She craved a connection more than material things, yet no boy caught her interest. Some tried, but their attempts fell flat. She wondered what blocked her from feeling drawn to anyone. Three years of reflection brought theories, but no concrete answers. She persists, questioning her heart's desires.

A calm day at home was shattered. Her parents, peaceful and rare argument-free, were no match for her own spirited energy. Today, she heard a scream from the kitchen, her mother's voice laced with pain. Running in, she found her mother on the floor, in immense agony. "Mom, what's wrong?!" she cried, helping her to the car. The drive to the hospital filled with the scent of disinfectant, fear, and her mother's pain. She rushed her in and called for help.

"She fell from a stool, trying to reach a vase," she explained to the worried faces around her mother. Her mother was taken away, and she sat worrying.

This research aimed to demonstrate that sticking to a "Mediterranean Diet" (Med diet), as indicated by a high "alternate Mediterranean (aMed) diet score", is linked to a reduced risk of chronic heart disease (CHD) and stroke, as well as stroke mortality. The aMed diet, a tweak on the Med diet, emphasizes higher consumption of plant foods like fruits, nuts, whole grains, and legumes, while limiting animal products and saturated fats. It also allows for moderate alcohol intake. Previous studies have shown a link between the Med diet and a lower risk of total and cardiovascular mortality, with an intervention trial showing it to be more effective than a low-fat diet in promoting weight loss and lowering cholesterol ratios in obese individuals. However, these studies did not focus on stroke or stroke mortality specifically.

This epidemiological study followed 74,886 women aged 38 to 63 without a history of CVD or diabetes, part of the Nurses' Health Study, a cohort of 121,700 female nurses in 11 US states. The authors calculated an aMed diet score six times between 1984 and 2004 using self-reported food frequency questionnaires (FFQs) designed to gauge nutrient intake during the preceding year. Over 95% of nurses remained in the study throughout the 20-year period. FFQs were validated, and reports of CHD, fatal CHD, and stroke were confirmed through medical or hospital records, autopsy, or death certificates. Where records were unavailable, cases were classified as "probable" and included, with about 17% of strokes and 24% of nonfatal myocardial infarcts so classified. Body mass index, smoking status, aspirin use, multivitamin intake, menopausal status, and use of postmenopausal hormones were calculated for each FFQ, and beginning in 1986, leisure-time physical activity was assessed.

Cumulative averages of the aMed score from the repeated FFQs were calculated to reduce random variation and better represent long-term dietary intake. Adjustments were made for confounders by considering age, smoking, BMI, menopausal status, postmenopausal hormone use, multivitamin intake, alcohol intake, physical activity, and aspirin use.

Cox proportional-hazard modeling was employed to examine the relationship between an aMed score and the risk of CHD and stroke, with separate models for fatal and nonfatal CHD and stroke types.

Higher adherence to the Mediterranean diet, as shown by a higher aMed diet score, was associated with a lower risk of CHD and stroke. Over 20 years of follow-up, 2391 CHD cases, 1763 stroke cases, and 1077 cardiovascular disease deaths were identified. Women in the top aMed quintile had a lower risk of both CHD and stroke compared to those in the bottom quintile (relative risk [RR], 0.71).

In the year 2007, the United States of America plunged into a devastating financial abyss. Unemployment soared, the housing market crumbled, and many of America’s most prominent corporations were left in shambles. This economic downturn continues to this day, prompting us to ask: what caused the crisis, and how can we prevent it from happening again? In essence, the financial crisis was born from reckless and shortsighted political decisions that coerced banks and corporations into granting sub-prime loans in a fragile and inadequate financial system. Meanwhile, Fannie Mae (FNMA) and Freddie Mac (FHLMC) were pushed to underwrite and repurpose these mortgages into CDO’s and CDS’s. When borrowers defaulted on these loans, the banks found themselves short on capital reserves, passing the chaos to the repackaged mortgages they had sold, and ultimately across the entire economy.

The seeds of this tragedy were planted during the Clinton administration in 1999, as the President sought a second term. To boost his popularity, he loosened lending restrictions, unwittingly setting the stage for the sub-prime crisis seven years later. Steven Holmes of the New York Times warned in 1999, “Fannie Mae, the nation’s largest mortgage underwriter, faced increasing pressure from the Clinton Administration to expand home loans to low and moderate-income individuals, while also coping with shareholder demands to maintain its remarkable profit growth.” Holmes accurately predicted the consequences of these actions, stating, “But the government-subsidized corporation could face financial trouble in an economic downturn, potentially requiring a government bailout similar to the savings and loan industry in the 1980s.” As mentioned earlier, and as Holmes foresaw, ill-advised lending led to the economic collapse.

Numerous factors contributed to the economic freefall, one of which was the complex and new mortgage structures. Adjustable-rate mortgages, mortgage-backed securities, and collateralized debt obligations (CDO’s) were heavily used in the years leading up to the crisis, further connecting various sectors of the economy to the housing market. This excessive leveraging left U.S. households and financial markets extremely exposed to price fluctuations.

Indeed, the housing bubble burst, leaving financial institutions that had invested in mortgage-backed securities reeling. The top five U.S. investment banks collectively reported $4.1 trillion dollars in mortgage debts in 2007, amounting to around 30% of America’s GDP. As a result, Bear Sterns and Merrill Lynch were sold at a bargain, Lehman Brothers was dismantled, and Goldman Sachs and Morgan Stanley were forced to become heavily regulated commercial banks. Fannie and Freddie, collectively holding $5 trillion in mortgage debt, were placed under government control in September 2008.

Ah, exposition. That section where you flex your writerly muscles and wow your audience with a barrage of words. Or the part where your readers hit the snooze button or click "Back" while you're mid-sentence. Dr. Merlin's been known to shout at her screen when she finds herself mired in a muddle of too much information, and it's not even the good kind.

Exposition is the little devil on your shoulder, whispering to get the boring stuff out of the way so you can get to the good parts. Not to be confused with the devil on the other shoulder, telling you to share every minuscule detail about each character's backstory.

Exposition means spelling out what happened, typically in straightforward prose. In movies, it's that one character dumping a bunch of info on another, like "The Rime of the Ancient Mariner." In fiction, it's the author doing the dumping.

Here's an example. You read that the heroine met her love at a particular place and time, wedded him in a grand ceremony, and he was killed before her eyes. You wouldn't expect a two-page exposition, during which they only speak a couple of lines each. You'd expect the author to spend time on the husband's character, showing you through his words and actions how much he loves his wife. Likewise, you'd want to see glimpses of the heroine's life and how her husband's presence enriched it. This would let you grieve his death along with her, and connect with her more deeply.

In other words, you'd want something more than just "They met, they married, he died."

As a writer, you need to give that something more. (*looks at metaphor, sighs, plunges onward*) It's tempting to rush past certain things. Maybe you're introducing a new character and you know he used to be in the Air Force, now runs a gas station, and has a certain fondness for Eggs Benedict. You need to show, not tell. You need to make it your reader's business to care about these details, or they'll promptly tune out and leave you to your navel-gazing.

I caught up on two news broadcasts from Columbus, Ohio. The first one, on NBC 4 this morning (August 13, 2011), had a live segment about a man in Ashley, Ohio who had stabbed his wife. Her name wasn't mentioned, but his was Shad Hostettler. His mug shot was shown, and he looked like a typical villain. The story was given about two minutes, which seemed appropriate given it was still unfolding. The details stated he stabbed her multiple times and was arrested.

The second story was about an early morning shooting of Travis Buyers, an 18-year-old in the Sharon Woods area. He was critically injured, and no arrests or suspects had been made yet. The SWAT Team was investigating. This story was brief, which I noticed is typical when a minority is the victim. I've noticed this pattern for years: when a white person is a crime victim, the media goes into a frenzy, but when the victim is a minority, they're lucky to get a mention.

The next story was about a bullet hole found in a Med-Flight helicopter. Details were given about the incident's location and the .22 caliber rifle used. Crime-Stoppers offered a $5,000 reward for information leading to the shooter's arrest.

The next story was a teaser about rain and thunderstorms predicted for Saturday afternoon, with temperatures in the mid to low eighties for the weekend.

Another story was about a robbery at a Clime Road UDF in Columbus. A dark-skinned black man, wearing a hoodie and about six-foot tall, robbed the store. They spent an unusual amount of time emphasizing his race and appearance.

Finally, there was a story about Rene Rodriguez, a convicted drug kingpin from Texas. He was sentenced for conspiring to distribute large amounts of marijuana to Ohio. Instead of saying 25 years prison, they said "300 months." I'm not sure why they used this phrasing. They also mentioned he was Hispanic, which didn't seem relevant to the story.

The bond between brothers is one that's unbreakable and irrevocable. It's a bond that holds deep emotions like love, pride, jealousy, and cruelty. Brothers, more than anyone else, understand each other and can see themselves reflected in their brother. In times of great distress, this bond shines through, whether it be for good or evil, with a great emotional cost. Understanding this bond also means dealing with the consequences it brings. When one looks into their brother's eyes, they don't see others' perceptions, but their true self. Their actions and the consequences they face reveal their true character. In "The Scarlet Ibis," two brothers explore this theme and its accompanying emotions. Through a lush, detailed landscape, they embark on a fruitless journey, with disappointment and pride clashing in the end. Only one brother survives. The theme is conveyed through the protagonist Doodle's direct characterization and his interactions with his brother, as well as the narrator's perspective, which shows Doodle's complex feelings and the world around him. Doodle's actions can be summed up by pride. From their first outing to their final, fateful one, Doodle felt resentment towards his brother, wishing he could teach him his worldly skills like holding breath, running, jumping, and climbing the vines in Old Woman Swamp. He wanted a brother to race with to Horsehead Landing and perch with in the top fork of the great pine behind the barn. Doodle’s condition made it nearly impossible for him to survive, much less participate in vigorous activity. This harsh reality crushed Doodle's dreams. He even contemplated killing Doodle by suffocating him with a pillow, showing his anger. However, his heart melted when Doodle smiled at him, proving his love for his brother was strong.

The human brain is a complex and ingenious information-processing system. As technology evolved from primitive to modern times, so did the metaphors used to describe the brain. Initially, it was likened to a wax tablet, then a sheet of papyrus, then a book, and most recently, a computer. As you delve into the mysteries of the brain, remember that these metaphors are limited in their usefulness and can often lead to misconceptions.

Information processing begins with input from the senses, which convert physical stimuli such as touch, heat, sound waves, or light particles into electrochemical signals. The brain's algorithms then transform this sensory information, using both bottom-up and top-down processing. For instance, when you see a picture of a black box on a white background, bottom-up processing assembles simple data like color, orientation, and the object's borders to identify it as a box. Top-down processing, in this case, aids in recognizing the object as a black box rather than a hole in the background.

Once processed, an attention filter determines the signal's importance and guides which cognitive processes should engage with it. For example, though your brain processes every blade of grass when you look at your shoes, a healthy attention filter keeps you from noticing them individually. However, you might pick out your name spoken in a noisy room. There are many stages of processing, and attention repeatedly modulates these results.

To process information, the brain must first store it. Various types of memory include sensory, working, and long-term. Initial encoding differs for each type of sensory stimulus. For example, verbal input can be encoded structurally (how it looks), phonemically (how it sounds), or semantically (what it means). Once stored, information in working memory, which lasts about 20 seconds, is maintained by an electrical signal looping through specific neurons. Information in long-term memory is hypothesized to be maintained by the structure of certain proteins.

Several models describe how knowledge is organized in the brain. Some are based on how humans retrieve memories, others on computer science, and others on neurophysiology. The semantic network model suggests that concepts are represented as nodes, with links based on relatedness. For instance, "chair" might be linked to "table," which can be linked to "wooden," and so forth.

Aldous Huxley is highly critical of the impending dangers posed by technology and capitalism, as seen in his novel Brave New World. The society in the book values community over individuality and is conditioned from birth to seek instant gratification. Citizens are essentially pawns in a grand scheme, bound by the World Controller's ideology. Viewing the novel through the lens of Marxist theology, one can see Huxley's worries about the development of these systems. Terms such as homogeny and reification, central to Marxism, emphasize the novel's critique of the shortcomings in the economic system of Huxley's time.

Capitalism is mocked through the Marxist concept of false consciousness, where the common folk are blind to their true economic standing, focusing instead on personal gain. This is achieved through ideological control of the working class, evident in the conditioning seen in Brave New World. Lower classes like Delta and Gamma have no true agency, their desire to consume and indulge driven by hypnopædia. The World Controller manipulates this, reinforcing hegemony where the ruling class controls the lower classes without them realizing it. Few Alphas or Betas, like Bernard, do more than accept their place, and social interactions highlight the perceived oppression of capitalism.

In Brave New World, relationships between individuals are shallow and lack depth. Even among key characters, characters are defined by their superficial interactions. It seems Huxley suggests that technology and capitalism together strip man of free will and expression. Love and extremes of emotions are non-existent, interactions are merely superficial, as seen in men's comments about women and vice versa. The complacency of each class in their hierarchical status shows the socioeconomic impact of capitalism, emphasizing Marxist thought on the proletariat's false belief in their superiority so long as they continue to consume and obey.

I've been a student at University Park for around two and a half years now, which is roughly equivalent to four and a half semesters. Navigating the campus hasn't always been easy, especially for freshmen. I was placed in an East Halls dorm room during my first year, which was probably the furthest eastward point on campus, excluding the stadium and Bryce Jordan Center. Just getting to classes like those in Willard Building, near the center of campus, could take up to 25 minutes on foot, especially in the often harsh weather of State College. An alum I spoke to told me that not long ago, East Halls dorms were separated from the rest of the school by vast, unused fields. Now, that space is packed with sports facilities, new buildings like the Creamery and health services, and apartments. As our campus keeps expanding, moving between places becomes increasingly challenging. What's the best solution? A bike, but just having one isn't enough. Students must ride them regularly, and the campus should be designed with cyclists in mind.

I discussed this with a friend who recently started cycling again after a several-year break. He mentioned, "Bikes are fantastic—they're the only efficient way to get around." Not only is cycling good for your health, but it can also save a lot of time. A simple bowl of oatmeal and a bit of physical exertion can take you up to 30 miles. Just like many other students, I now live off campus, almost as far from the center as some dorms. The best decision I made this year was getting a bike. Every day, I go to class in Thomas Building, which is around 25 minutes walk from my place. Riding a bike can cut that to just 5 minutes, assuming I pedal fast enough. The main issue is that Pollock Road, the most direct route to Thomas, isn't always bike-friendly. While walking has its merits, I simply don't have the time. Without a bike, walking would be my only viable option for getting to class, adding an extra 30-40 minutes each way. That's nearly two and a half extra hours every week, not counting other trips for classes, appointments, etc. That's more time than I can spare.

Culture plays a significant role in any negotiation. Culture can be defined as much by what it is not as what it actually is and what it signifies. Culture is not homogenous, nor is it a specific thing. It is also not singular or uniform. Statements such as “all Russians are stubborn” or “all Japanese are accommodating,” are inherently broad and overly simplistic. While the understanding of a culture’s generalizations are appropriate, it is much more productive to a negotiator to understand the significance of a culture to the matter at hand, and how that culture’s attitude can and will affect the table talks. When one approaches a foreign culture, one experiences it in a way that is relatable to his own culture, and comparisons necessarily arise. 

Attempting to understand a foreign culture or mindset can involve anything from studying its history to realizing its prejudices. Rather than judging or attempting to change a culture, one must simply accept it for what it is, and work within its boundaries, especially within the scope of negotiation, and most especially if one comes to the table with a weaker bargaining position. Likewise, if a negotiator finds himself on “away” territory, a respect for traditions and beliefs can only help in getting over any cultural barriers and move the negotiation forward.

It is important to note that culture does not necessarily limit itself to a national/international dichotomy. Most companies within a given nation establish their own corporate culture. For instance, a corporate culture might emphasize long hours in the office or a more relaxed schedule. Evidence of a corporate culture can be seen in employee dress codes, in communication style (direct v. indirect communication, delegation of duties), and hiring practices. Some companies encourage philanthropy at any level from employees, others restrict it to “company approved” charities or fundraisers. One need only look at the differences in American corporate culture from company to company (and indeed, intra-company diversity exists even from region to region, urban to suburban environments included) to appreciate the diversity of thought that can reside within a particular societal culture. Certain cultures are not nearly as stratified as American culture, and may appear more uniform to an outsider, but a similar exterior is simply a sign to dig deeper. 

Values are even more important to understand, because they provide the why of a culture. If saving face or communal harmony are valued within a culture, it is certain that a negotiator will not publicly shame his company or his superior in order to succeed at the negotiation table. Likewise, a negotiator from a culture which gives greater weight to a hard-driven bargain will not necessarily be driven to settle at the earliest opportunity. Taking these generalities into consideration is important before one gets to the negotiating table. However, a negotiator is well-served to learn something about his opponent on a personal level in order to make the negotiation effective.

“The fool hath said in his heart, ‘There is no God.’” The preceding quotation is seen first in Psalm 14 of the Christian Bible, and is found at the beginning of St. Anselm’s argument regarding the existence of God. This belief seems to also be held by the other author whom we will be discussing, Thomas Aquinas. Because each of their arguments is in defense of the same concept, and our challenge is to determine who’s is the better of the two, we must, for sake of brevity, begin with the presumption that they are both correct in their belief in the existence of God, specifically the God of the Bible. To allow for a God-type figure that may not resemble the one in whom our two authors believe would not permit us to appropriately compare their two arguments, as they are essentially in defense of one specific concept of God. That being said, I would suggest that while each of them brings up valid points, neither truly provides a holistic basis for belief in God.
	To illustrate this point, we will first examine the basic argument of St. Anselm. Anselm’s passage reflects a path of gaining understanding through faith, looking within one’s self to find proof of God. He explains that because God exists within our understanding, we cannot effectively conceive his nonexistence. While this concept, when spelled out in his terminology, is a bit tedious and at times unclear, the basic gist of it is that the proof for God lies within one’s own mind. St. Anselm is suggesting to us that we needn’t go beyond the confines of our own soul to find truth about God, but that the existence of this being is found to be true simply by examining that which we inherently know to be true within our own minds. Foreign evidence is presumably unnecessary. This concept of accepting that for which there is not an irrefutable body of empirical evidence is often referred to within Christian texts as faith.
	This idea is very different from that held by St. Thomas Aquinas. Aquinas instead suggests that the existence of God can be proven entirely through reason and empirical evidence, with no need for faith of any kind. Such an idea would be beneficial in evangelism, an important element of Christianity, because it would enable the recruiting of new converts without any dependency upon their willingness to accept something that cannot be proven. They could instead be persuaded by logic alone. St. Thomas elaborates on five different logical arguments supporting the existence of God: change, causation, contingency, degrees of excellence, and harmony. In each he essentially demonstrates that the proof of God lies in the logical necessity for God. If you are told that that you are missing one puzzle piece, and assemble the rest of the puzzle, logic dictates that you can know of the features and the existence of the missing piece without having to see it.

Many authors use different ways to give their readers a certain feeling or attitude toward
important subjects. Some of these techniques are more effective than others. F. Scott Fitzgerald uses
many of these different techniques in his novel The Great Gatsby. Sometimes, Fitzgerald pairs an
adjective and a noun together that do not usually fit that way to give readers a certain aura around a
subject. Other times, he applies meaning to a symbol, and then uses it for this same purpose.
Fitzgerald uses this last technique with many colors, including gold, green, white/gray and red/pink. In
his novel The Great Gatsby F. Scott Fitzgerald builds up meaning for colors, namely white/gray and
red/pink then later uses that meaning to give readers a certain reminder of a feeling around an
important object.
The meaning Fitzgerald builds up and uses for white/gray is uniformity, with white being a bit
nicer and higher class and gray being more older and faded. Fitzgerald sets up this meaning in the
beginning of the novel with constant uses of both. Daisy and Jordan are constantly “in white” (8)—in
fact, everyone is always wearing white: Nick wears “white flannels” (41) to Gatsby’s party, Tom wears
a “white shirt” (36) when he meets Myrtle, and Catherine is “powdered milky white” (30). In fact, the
only time people are not wearing white is when Nick is getting his impressions of Gatsby’s party: “the
halls... are gaudy with primary colors” (40). Fitzgerald further defines these two colors in coloring
many common, unimportant subjects these colors: as Nick goes to work, he goes “down the white
chasms of lower New York” (56), the names of people at Gatsby’s parties are now “gray names” (61)
on Nick’s timetable, Catherine’s apartment is “one slice in a long white cake of apartment-houses”—
uniformity (28). He also describes plain or common people or places as white or gray: Jordan and
Daisy had a “white girlhood” (19) together, there are “gray cars” and “gray land” (23) in the valley of
ashes, the “Italian child” in the railroad is “gray” (26), and the dog-seller is “a gray old man” (27).
After Fitzgerald adds enough meaning to white/gray, he uses them to signify unimportance or
uniformity to certain subjects. This using colors to show readers something first starts with Daisy.
After a long time without any significant use of either of these colors, Fitzgerald comes out describing
Daisy as “dressed in white” in “a little white roadster”; readers begin to see Daisy as less of a character,
more like just a uniform addition, something that Gatsby wants and longs for (74). Fitzgerald uses
more of this technique around Daisy to give this impression of Daisy being a more uniform addition,
for example, there is a “gray haze of Daisy’s fur collar” (18), and she is again in a “white” (115) dress
before Tom and Gatsby’s encounter.

San Diego County is very agriculturally productive, thanks to a mild, sunny climate. Common crops include: tomatoes, citrus, leafy greens, squash, broccoli, herbs, tree fruits like peaches and lemons, berries, honey, and peppers. There is a substantial market for organic community supported agriculture food in the San Diego area, with many local organizations having lengthy waiting lists. Organic eggs and milk are also popular. Many organic farms also provide tours of their agricultural operations as well as access for hiking, birdwatching, and other recreational activities. This is the type of operation that would allow the landowner to gain the benefits of government programs while improving habitat, thus allowing recreational use and creating an opportunity for farm tours and other programs for making money or for educational purposes.  
	In addition to filling a potentially lucrative niche market, the benefits of organic farming often include greater biodiversity in plants and wildlife in the area thanks to a lack of chemicals in the soil and water. However, organic farming has greater costs than conventional farming in some ways. It requires more intensive labor and management to remove pests and weeds and fertilize the soil without chemicals, and losses are often greater than with conventional methods, while a small organic farm also lacks the efficiency of scale of large operations. Practices not related to organic farming but beneficial to wildlife may also incur greater labor costs, including planting cover crops, strategic grazing rotation, invasive species removal, and active management of plant growth to provide specific conditions such as edge habitat or patches of open ground. Thus, there are many reasons why the landowner in this example might seek financial help or expertise in maximizing both profits and habitat quality.  
The land chosen for this scenario is a parcel adjacent to the town of Potrero, in unincorporated San Diego County, California. It is 160 acres of chaparral, nonnative Mediterranean grassland, and oak woodland next to to the Cleveland National Forest. It lies in the East County Southern Foothills ecoregion of the San Diego Multiple Species Conservation Plan. The plan is still being reviewed, but presently considers over a hundred species of plants and animals. Many are endangered, such as the Stephens' kangaroo rat, the mountain yellow-legged frog, several species of butterfly, and the California gnatcatcher; others are declining and may soon be listed, such as burrowing owls.
	This area was inhabited by Native Americans for untold centuries and was then settled by cattle ranchers and cordwood sellers in the late 1800's. This piece of land was part of an original homestead patent and so was probably used for grazing and/or wood production for many of the intervening decades.
	 chose a piece of property from a real estate website and researched available government programs to see what options a small farmer might realistically have for mitigating costs and preserving wildlife-friendly operations.  As a model of what somebody farming this land might attempt to achieve, I located an organic farm in the same area.

There is a bond between brothers; an unbreakable, irrevocable bond. Within that bond lie many emotions: love, pride, jealousy, and cruelty, just to name a few. Brothers understand one another, far more than anyone else with that kind of bond, and they can only see themselves when looking at their brother. It is when a situation is at its most dire when the true nature of this bond shines through, be it good or evil. When these emotions become clear, they carry with them great a cost. Part of understanding the emotions born of this fraternal link is dealing with the consequences that they bring. When one can look a brother in the eye and see within that person their own reflection, they see themselves not as others see them, but as they truly are. In their actions and the consequences of those actions is where their true character lies.  In “The Scarlet Ibis”, two brothers explore this theme, and all of the raging emotions that accompany it. Throughout a lush, vividly described landscape, these two boys set out on a futile journey. Bitter disappointment clashes with intense pride in the climactic scene, and only one brother escapes with his life. The theme is expressed through direct characterization of the protagonist, Doodle, and their interactions with each other, as well as through the narrator’s point of view, which communicates the complex feelings experienced by the protagonist and his view of the world around him, both of which are heavy influences on his actions.
	The protagonist’s actions can all be summed up by one key emotion: pride. From the time he and his little brother, Doodle, first go out together, to their final, fateful excursion, the protagonist feels resentment towards Doodle. He had wanted a brother whom he could teach all of his worldly skills, like “…holding my breath, running, jumping, or climbing the vines in Old Woman Swamp…” He wanted a brother who could fill the role of “…someone to race to Horsehead Landing…and someone to perch with in the top fork of the great pine behind the barn…” Obviously these things are impossible, given Doodle’s condition. Doodle was born with an extremely weak heart, making in unlikely he would even survive. Even then, it was nearly impossible that he would ever participate in vigorous physical activity. What a blow to the young protagonist, his head filled with wild fantasies, to have all of those dreams crushed in an instant. In fact, he is even shown to bear some anger towards the small child, as he recalls beginning to contemplate killing him by suffocating him with a pillow. What kind of child would have the presence of mind to consider infanticide? However, his heart melts when the small child smiles at him. Such a simple act gave the protagonist such hope! This shows that his conviction probably was not very strong. In the back of his mind, he had an instinctive love for his brother.

The human brain is a complicated, creative information-processing system. As technology advanced from primitive to modern, the metaphors used to describe the brain also advanced. Initially, it was compared to a wax tablet, then to a sheet of papyrus, then to a book, and most recently, to a computer. As you learn about the brain, keep in mind that the usefulness of these metaphors is limited and can lead to erroneous conclusions.
Information processing starts with input from the sensory organs, which transform physical stimuli such as touch, heat, sound waves, or photons of light into electrochemical signals. The sensory information is repeatedly transformed by the algorithms of the brain in both bottom-up and top-down processing. For example, when looking at a picture of a black box on a white background, bottom-up processing puts together very simple information such as color, orientation, and where the borders of the object are – where the color changes significantly over a short space – to decide that you are seeing a box. Top-down processing uses the decisions made at some steps of the bottom-up process to speed up your recognition of the box. Top-down processing in this example might help you identify the object as a black box rather than a box-shaped hole in the white background.
Once information is processed to a degree, an attention filter decides how important the signal is and which cognitive processes it should be made available to. For example, although your brain processes every blade of grass when you look down at your shoes, a healthy attention filter prevents you from noticing them individually. In contrast, you might pick out your name, even when spoken in a noisy room. There are many stages of processing, and the results of processing are modulated by attention repeatedly.
In order for the brain to process information, it must first be stored. There are multiple types of memory, including sensory, working, and long-term. First, information is encoded. There are types of encoding specific to each type of sensory stimuli. For example, verbal input can be encoded structurally, referring to what the printed word looks like, phonemically, referring to what the word sounds like, or semantically, referring to what the word means. Once information is stored, it must be maintained. Some animal studies suggest that working memory, which stores information for roughly 20 seconds, is maintained by an electrical signal looping through a particular series of neurons for a short period of time. Information in long-term memory is hypothesized to be maintained in the structure of certain types of proteins.
There are numerous models of how the knowledge is organized in the brain, some based on the way human subjects retrieve memories, others based on computer science, and others based on neurophysiology. The semantic network model states that there are nodes representing concepts, and that the nodes are linked based on their relatedness. For example, in a semantic network, “chair” might be linked to “table,” which can be linked to “wooden,” and so forth.

In 2007, the United States of America fell into a crushing financial crisis. Unemployment increased, the housing market crashed, and many of America’s largest and most important corportations were left in ruin. This recession persists today, so we must ask the question: how did this crisis occur, and how can we stop it? In short, the financial crisis was created by selfish and naïve political decision-making that pressured banks and firms into issuing sub-prime loans into an already immature and unsufficient financial infrastructure. Meanwhile, Fannie Mae (FNMA) and Freddie Mac (FHLMC) were pressured to underwite and repackage these mortgages into CDO’s and CDS’. When borrowers defaulted on these loans, the banks were short on capital reserve and transferred this chaos onto the repacked mortgages that they had sold, and on to the rest of the economy.
	The financial crisis had its roots in 1999 of the Clinton era, as the President was aiming for a second term in office. He sought to extend his presidential tenure by augmenting his popularity. To accomplish this the Clinton administration relaxed lending restrictions, which helped to set the grim stage for the sub-prime crisis seven years later.  Steven Holmes of the New York Times reported in 1999, “Fannie Mae, the nation's biggest underwriter of home mortgages, has been under increasing pressure from the Clinton Administration to expand mortgage loans among low and moderate income people and felt pressure from stock holders to maintain its phenomenal growth in profits.” Holmes would go on to correctly foresee the consequences of these actions: “But the government-subsidized corporation may run into trouble in an economic downturn, prompting a government rescue similar to that of the savings and loan industry in the 1980s.” As detailed in the introduction, and as Holmes foresaw, ill-advised lending would certainly lead to the meltdown of the economy.
	Many factors combined to throw the economy into tailspin, one of which was the new and complex structure of mortgages. Adjustable-rate mortgages, mortgage-backed securities, and collateralized debt obligations (CDO’s) were all used extensively in the years leading up to the crisis, and only served to intertwine more sectors of the economy into the housing market. This led to U.S. households, and financial markets in general, to overleverage themselves in the housing market, leaving them extremely vulnerable to even small changes in price. 
	Indeed, the housing bubble burst, and the financial institutions that had bought these mortgage-backed securities were spited. The top five U.S. investment banks all together reported $4.1 trillion dollars of mortgage debts in 2007, which accounted for about 30% of the USA’s GDP. In the end, Bear Sterns and Merrill Lynch were sold exceptionally cheap, Lehman Brothers was dismantled, and Goldman Sachs and Morgan Stanley were forced to become commercial banks subjected to intense regulation. Fannie and Freddie were $5 trillion in mortgage debt, and were placed under government control in September 2008.

Ah, exposition.  That place in your story where you stretch your little writer's wings and take flight, astounding one and all with your magnetic, nay magical prose.  Or the part where your readers fall asleep and/or hit the "Back" button while cursing your name.  Dr. Merlin has been known to shout at her monitor when she finds herself in the middle of Too Much Information, and not even in the fun way.

Exposition is not your friend.

My gentle readers already know the basic writing tip, "Show, don't tell," but Dr. Merlin still stumbles into long passages of text where nothing happens, or worse, too much.  Exposition is the little devil sitting on your shoulder that says to get the history out of the way to get to the good parts (not to be confused with the devil sitting on the other shoulder urging the author to tell her audience every single detail of the childhoods of each character).

Exposition means telling the audience what happened, typically in simple prose.  In film, the exposition happens when one character tells another a core-dump of information ala "The Rime of the Ancient Mariner."  In fiction, the author's doing the telling.

An example is in order.  As you are reading a story, you are told that the heroine met her beloved at such a place and time, that they were married in a gala fashion, and that her husband was murdered in front of her eyes.  You would not expect this entire sequence to take two pages, during which time both he and she only get two lines of dialogue each.
