A method for counting whorls is seen below.  First,‭ ‬the shell should be viewed from the apical view and then it should be determined where the first suture begins.  A line can be then drawn dividing the shell into two parts.  Whorls are counted from this line,‭ ‬and are estimated to a quarter of a whorl.

A shell can be viewed as a series of apertures that travel through time and space as the animal accretes‭ (‬i.e. builds‭) ‬its shell.  It is possible to trace the path of the aperture via coordinates of the center of each whorl’s aperture as well as the horizontal and vertical radius of the aperture.

This trajectory can be graphically and mathematically represented.  Once a mathematical formulation is made,‭ ‬it is then possible to vary parameters and modify the mollusk’s skeletogenesis.

The rate of neonatal and infant mortality in Indonesia remained rather static for the last ten years.  While the country is on track to meet many of the Millennium Development Goals, such as the water and sanitation targets, the rates of improvement for child and maternal health are woefully short of the improvements needed to meet their target goals by 2015.  The multiple reasons for these shortcomings will be discussed below, and point to a need to strengthen the health system rather than focus on programmatic interventions.
	Indonesia has made improvements in the number of births with a skilled health worker attending, with 72% of births now meeting this target.  That being said, this category still includes traditional workers, such as midwives, who cannot provide medical interventions should the pregnancy be complicated (hence the large percentage of maternal deaths caused by hemorrhage).  In other words,  the improvements made in this particular indicator are somewhat misleading and there is still much work to be done.  In addition, there has been a decline in the percentage of diarrheal cases in children under five years treated by a health professional.  While data on postnatal care is incomplete, it is clear that this area is also of concern, with low rates across the country.
	Cesarian-section rates are still lower than should be expected, around 4%.  The c-section rates additionally point to another concerning issue.  While the rate of c-section is 7% in urban settings, it is only 2% in rural.  This points to the problem of equity of coverage across the country.  Clearly access to healthcare services is focused around urban areas.  Another issue of access concerns vertical equity.  There is a 27% gap in service utilization between the poorest and richest quintiles.  Clearly the poor are finding it much more difficult to access healthcare services, likely due to out of pocket costs.
	In discussing next steps towards improving neonatal and maternal care indicators, the most basic question is how to most effectively address the lack of service.  Specifically, should Indonesia develop program-specific approaches or strengthen the overall health system without focusing on pre and post-pregnancy care for the mother and child.  There is no question that programmatic approaches to solve the problems outlined above are attractive.  Not only do “vertical approaches” that target one sector of improvements have much more targeted, manageable objectives, they also generally generate faster results.  There are some drawbacks to keep in mind, however.  One major drawback is that investing heavily in programming for one particular area of the health sector often means that funding for other areas suffers and human resources will flock towards working in that area that has more resources (the effect of international funding to HIV/AIDS and its effect on the family planning sector is one example).  In addition, running multiple parallel programs for one area results in duplication of services that are also uncoordinated between programs.  This leads to an increase in forms and paperwork for supplies and funding.

‎	‏The classification of Popular Music has grown over the past‭ ‬100‭ ‬years to include so many genres that it is difficult to definitively list them all. Complicating matters,‭ ‬most if not all genres—rap,‭ ‬rock,‭ ‬country,‭ ‬jazz,‭ ‬folk,‭ ‬just to name a few—have spawned multiple sub and sub-sub genres within their domain.  Arguably the sub-genre of Heavy Metal rock has become one of the most diverse and expressive genres of all popular music in the past‭ ‬40‭ ‬years. It is expressive because it displays a wide range of emotions,‭ ‬although they tend to lean toward the darker side of the spectrum. It is diverse in that quite soon after the beginnings of the genre,‭ ‬people started to realize that it had real flexibility and started to take advantage of it to create their own sub-genre,‭ ‬which then was followed by sub-sub-genres,‭ ‬and the chain continues until today. 

Today we have reached a point in the heavy metal movement where there are so many niches of groups that it is hard to determine what exactly heavy metal is. It has grown to incorporate so many themes from other genres,‭ ‬but like everything else,‭ ‬it spawned from somewhere. In order to properly understand the metal music that exists everywhere today,‭ ‬one must first understand what the metal movement is,‭ ‬and why it’s a movement rather than just a genre.

‎	‏Metal is,‭ ‬in many ways,‭ ‬a movement defined by darkness. Metal can be considered a‭ “‬music of more‭”—‬more bass,‭ ‬more volume,‭ ‬more violence,‭ ‬more theatricality. Less primitivism,‭ ‬more chops‭; ‬people in metal bands really know how to play their instrument,‭ ‬and it comes through in the music. Metal is also—although it may not come as a surprise—a movement that is heavily drug induced. There was a psychedelic drug boom in the mid-70‭’‬s that led to people getting crazier,‭ ‬leading to them to make crazy,‭ ‬other-worldly records,‭ ‬using the drugs as a scapegoat for their creation. It possesses many dark,‭ ‬visceral qualities,‭ ‬which was very new to the music scene because a large amount of popular music had qualities that weren’t true to the darker side of the emotional spectrum. Also,‭ ‬later generations of metal have taken some of their influence from the dark,‭ ‬visceral qualities that were so present in the Romantic Era. Lyrics such as the following express the darkness that is such a staple of the movement:‭ (‬Byrne‭)‬


	
These lyrics from Helter Skelter display the darker side of the Beatles. It exhibits an up and down,‭ ‬supposedly that of drugs. This song is considered by some to be one of the first Heavy Metal songs. It was a response to a Rolling Stones song that was also on the heavier,‭ ‬darker side. The Beatles wanted to prove that they could be just as heavy as the Stones,‭ ‬so they put that song on‭ ‬The White Album.

A few decades before the Surrealist artists began painting their dreamlike works, the artist Henri Rousseau was carefully crafting his own dreams, literally and figuratively. The Dream, a 1910 painting by the famous Post-Impressionist artist, represents not only a woman in awe at the wonders of the land she visits within a dream, but also Rousseau’s own personal dreams and goals as a painter. Since beginning his work, he dreamed of recognition, acceptance, and praise by other artists and art lovers, and found that he was faced with a difficult internal dilemma to achieve this aspiration. The Dream is Henri Rousseau’s work that best reflects his career-long internal struggle: to either conform to or mimic certain styles of painting in order to be accepted by the critical art world he so adored, or to allow himself to be creatively independent and unique, leaving his own path as he went.
Before one can analyze The Dream through this perspective, one must first be somewhat familiar with Rousseau’s biographical story. Henri Rousseau was born on May 21, 1844, in the town of Laval in northwest France. His father was a tinsmith and hardware dealer who “enjoyed bourgeois prosperity” (Shattuck 47). Growing up, he received no formal training in the arts; instead, he was employed until the age of forty working for France as a gabelou, or employee of the municipal toll service, although he received the misnomer sobriquet of douanier, a customs inspector (Shattuck 46). The death of his first wife, Clémence, which followed the deaths of eight infant children, left Rousseau with only one child, a daughter named Julia, and immense grief (Shattuck 49). He therefore hoped to take refuge in a new life and pursued painting to offer him comfort and fresh beginnings. Unlike contemporary colleagues of Rousseau who sentimentalize and romanticize the peasant in painting, he is essentially a folk painter and has the hopes and dreams of the average member of his class.
Rousseau’s obsession with being accepted by the art world is somewhat understandable when evaluated in context: as discussed, he was not only uneducated in the ways of formal painting and began his career at a much older age, but he was producing works at the same time as many other talented and better-known modern artists. Though working for many years already, Rousseau did not begin to receive proper recognition for his art until around the same time that Matisse had begun crafting a reputation as an artist. In the book Modern French Painters, author Jan Gordon asserts that the two, while technically competitors in the art arena, were different not only in style and subject matter but also their reasons for painting in the first place: “Matisse was a painter who conceived a terror of painting in a trite way, while Rousseau’s desire was to paint a picture so conventional that he would be admitted to the Artiste Français” (92).

Many a great thinker has postulated an intimate connection between ethics and aesthetics, between truth and beauty. I believe that at a fundamental level there is a reason for this. As John Keats says in “Ode on a Grecian Urn”, “Beauty is truth, truth beauty- That is all / Ye know on earth, and all ye need to know.” Much of what we know in life is learned via education or experience. However, we seem to appreciate ethics and aesthetics, as Keats implies, without being taught in these expected ways. Both ethics and aesthetics are an attempt to describe rather then prescribe. Our studies of morality and beauty are, for the most part, attempts to explain why a piece of art or literature is beautiful, or why an action is moral, rather than a set of rules for judging, or creating, good art or moral behavior. 
	More to the point, criticism of art or morals is never able to fully capture the essence of what is good or what is beautiful. A conversation about the worth of da Vinci's Mona Lisa, for example, may center around concepts like foreground, background, contrast, or cultural context, but in the end, these do not describe why it is good art. Rather, when one is asked about a favorite work of art or literature it is common to hear a phrase similar to, “There's just something about it” preceding a more complex or critical explanation. I believe that both art and morals can never be completely reduced to a description of their qualities. As Flannery O'Connor says, “A story is a way to say something that can't be said any other way . . . you tell a story because a statement would be inadequate.” No matter how completely we describe the properties of a work of literature, there is something transcendent which is still left. I believe that ethics has this same property. As Wittgenstein says, “It is clear that ethics cannot be expressed. / Ethics is transcendental. / . I suggest that it is this “something”, this je ne sais quoi, which is art and morality's most powerful attribute, and that this transcendental nature of both ethics and aesthetics provides a connection point between them.
	I believe that morality and art are so closely related because we experience both of them most powerfully at a noumenally, to use a Kantian term. They impact us at a level that can be experienced, but not fully explained. This link is even stronger when it comes to the art of literature. As McKean says, “What most distinguishes literature from the other arts, what is, in truth, unique about the art, is its moral quality. It may be that moral standards are inappropriate to other arts, music, for instance, but they seem to be as relevant to literature as they are to life itself. Living necessarily involves values. . . . Literature is important to us precisely because of the values we find there” .

The Germany of today is considered a strong force, a united country with its own blend of culture from within the shadows of the alps in München, all the way to Baltic sea city of Kiel.  The same culture can be felt from Köln on the river Rhine, through the centre of Germany to the Saxon city of Dresden located on the Elbe. With such a unique culture, it shouldn't be surprising that Germany as we now know it comes from several different sources, and tribes. 

Germania is the ancestral land of the Germans. The origins of the name are highly disputed among scholars and historians. Tacitus claimed that the name came from a Germanic Tribe known then as Tungrians, and that they had previously been known as Germans before they crossed the Rhine and battled the Gaulish forces (Tacitus, 98.) Julius Caesar first used the word “Germanus” in his commentary on the Gallic Wars where he put down the Gauls and battled with Germanic tribes which crossed the Rhine often under mischievous premisses. He took this word from The Gauls themselves, and used it to distinguish between those which he had conquered (The Gauls) and those which he had not. While the origin is uncertain, some believe it referred to a neighbor in the Gaulish language. In the first chapter, of his first book on these wars, Julius Caesar notes: “Germans, who dwell beyond the Rhine, with whom they (The Gauls) are continually waging war.....They contend with the Germans in almost daily battles.” (Julius Caesar, 50-40 BC) Others claim the meaning comes from the spear that they used in warfare, known as a ger (O.E.D, 2010), or perhaps from the Old Irish word garim meaning “to shout”, which indicated the Germans were loud, or noisy. (Names of Germany) 

 The early Roman historian Tacitus recorded in his AD 98 writing “De Origine et situ Germanorum”, which told of the origins of the Germans, that “I should regard (The Germans) as aboriginal, and not mixed at all with other races through immigration or intercourse. For, in former times it was not by land but on shipboard that those who sought to emigrate would arrive.......Who would leave Asia, or Africa, for Italy for Germany, with its wild country, its inclement skies, its sullen manners and aspect, unless indeed it were his home?(SIC)” (Tacitus, 98) 

And who would leave Rome for Germania? Certainly not the Romans, not yet at least. They would send out their conquests into the lands of Germania for goods, and lead the occasional land campaign but in the end they mostly returned back home to their sprawling empire. So as the Germanic tribes began appearing in the middle of the first century, they lived on the borders of the Roman Empire and traded their goods taken from the land, and their skills by serving within the ranks of the Roman army, (Ozment, 2005 pg. 17.)

The play Twelfth Night seems to say that although disguise is in fact useful in perpetrating long bouts of deception, in the end a person must reject that newly formed guise, or else risk losing themselves forever in the process. A big problem with ending a deception, however, is that one may find themselves alienated in the process. Therefore, in the end, one must decide between one’s own self preservation, or the preservation of relationships with those around them. For although some will respond neutrally to discovering that they’ve been tricked, still others will not take the deception so lightly, and will be likely be offended by the whole charade.
The topic of deception in gender role reversal is especially problematic, because it brings up many side issues, perhaps the most important one being, why? Why does the subject feel the need to shirk their own identity and take up a disguise in the form of the opposite gender? In Viola’s case, it is obviously a form of self protection.: “I’ll bring you to a captain in this town/ Where lie my maiden weeds, by whose gentle help/ I was preserved to serve this noble count…” (5.1.247-249)
Having newly arrived in a foreign land, Viola feels it necessary to pretend to be a man to protect herself from would be attackers. Viola’s plan works, but it also alienates her from the women around her, cutting her off from an important support system. To make matters worse, she is apparently so convincing at appearing to be a man that Olivia confuses her with Sebastian, and in effect falls in love with her. “Whither, my lord? Cesario, husband, stay.” (5.1.138) On top of that, she also has to deal with suppressed romantic desires between her and Orsino: “Boy, thou hast said to me a thousand times/ Thou never shouldst love woman like to me.” (5.1. 260-261)
Although this may be a somewhat progressive attitude, to the modern reader, Twelfth Night may be seen as an illustration of how deception may help facilitate the unveiling of suppressed emotions, especially in the cases of Olivia and Orsino. Certain passages seem to hint that the aforesaid characters may have unexpressed subconscious desires that the appearance of Viola/Cesario forces them to deal with. For instance, is Olivia attracted to Cesario because Cesario appears to be a man, or does Olivia really secretly harbor feelings for women? One would argue that this is probably not the case, because Shakespeare’s character Olivia seems more likely to be parodying those people of his time period who judge others only upon their looks. 
This is evidenced by the ease with which Olivia switches her romantic ardors from Cesario to Sebastian, and begins to regard Cesario/Viola as family rather than a love interest: “A sister, you are she.” (5.1.315)

German colonial rule has been noted by various observers for its brutality, notably with respect to the genocide of the Ovaherero and Nama in German South West Africa. Of course nothing so broad as an entire colonial empire can be accounted for by such a simple description. The German colonial empire was as varied in policies and ruling style as it was in geography. Educational provision across the colonies was similarly diverse. When the British took over German East Africa (Tanganyika) in 1919, they found a large population of educated and literate Africans. German educational efforts in Kamerun and other colonies were also praised by contemporary authors. 
The situation in South West Africa (present-day Namibia) presented a stark contrast.  Unlike in East Africa, where the government established state schools and played a prominent role in the education of the natives, in South West Africa the task of native education was left almost entirely to missionary societies that received limited government support. The government did however invest significant resources towards the education of Europeans in the colony, establishing s system of state schools as well as more heavily supporting and regulating missionary schools. These educational policies had longstanding effects on South West Africa, even after German rule. While other German colonies boasted significant numbers of literate and educated Africans, in South West Africa “the overwhelming majority of the population remained untouched, uneducated, and illiterate.” Various social, political, and economic factors led to the divergent experience of South West Africa. This paper seeks to expand the discussion by identifying these factors and paying particular attention to new research on the attitudes of settlers and colonial authorities to native Africans.
There is a wealth of literature dealing with education in the German colonial empire specifically. Most of these sources are in German and were written in the early twentieth century, during or shortly after the period of German colonial rule. The aim of early works was primarily to describe the features of educational systems in these colonies. Later writings in English expanded the discourse through comparative studies of education in the various German colonies and more detailed analyses of specific aspects of education. These studies illustrated significant differences in the educational systems of different colonies. The most prominent work to explicitly address the topic of this paper is Cohen’s study of education in South West Africa and East Africa. Cohen compares the educational systems of the two colonies and discusses the factors that account for the differences between them. According to Cohen, the large settler population of South West Africa explains many of the distinguishing aspects of the colony’s educational system.
Compared to Germany’s other colonial possessions, South West Africa had a moderately temperate climate, although much of the territory is covered by arid desert. The European population of South West Africa reflected the relatively hospitable conditions. By 1913 nearly 15,000 whites lived in South West Africa, while only 5,336 lived in the colony with the next largest settler population, East Africa.

The United States of America and Mexico are an example of two nations which at one time were beset by an enduring rivalry which spanned 57 years, from 1836 to 1893. (Diehl and Goerts 2000 p. 145).  The high-water mark of this rivalry was the Mexican-American War of 1846-1848, where the United States attacked and defeated Mexico and secured for itself Texas and the American Southwest as new territory.  Many other clashes happened between the two nations, finally abating just before the First World War.   The rivalry began as Americans and Mexicans clashed on key issues such as religion, culture and tradition and had a major clash of material interests (Schmitt 1974 p. 30-31).   
	This is not unlike many other nations who have an enduring rivalry with a neighbor.  Nations which share a border tend to have clashes of interests which lend to the creation of rival positions between the nations.  The United States and Mexico are not unlike many other enduring rivalries between nations which share a common border.  David M. Pletcher (1977) states that “Only in Mexico and Cuba can one find long-lasting overarching American diplomatic problems” (p. 41).  Indeed, both of these nations are geographically close to the United States and have been rivals to the United States, while other nations in Latin America enjoy and have enjoyed good relations with the United States.   
	Religious issues created a rift between the two nations, a problem which has beset many nations through history.  Sally Frahm (2001) states that ”if in the twentieth century Americans were opposed to fascism and communism, in the eighteenth and nineteenth they were opposed to Catholicism and monarchy”  (p.86).  Not unlike the Cold War’s rivalry between the United States and the Soviet Union was part ideological struggle and part a competition over interests each nation deemed vital. In this case, however, the ideological struggles weren’t based on the political structure but on instead the religious preferences of the United States and Mexico.  This distrust grew from the distrust between the English and Spanish.  Inheriting these feelings of distrust from their former colonial rulers was a major obstacle in the establishment of amiable foreign relations between the United States and Mexico.
	Diehl and Goerts (2000) list 17 disputes between Mexico and the United States in the 57-year rivalry period.   The majority of disputes between the rivalry period described by Diehl and Goerts are territorial issues relating to border raids from Mexican territory into Mexico and other frontier problems.  Border raids by bandits and outlaws from on American border towns were a major problem which remained until both the United States and Mexico exerted military force on their borders (Schmitt 1974 p. 97).  
Schmitt (1974) explains the rivalry between the two nation began to abate as “Mexico became clearly dependent on the United States in a substantial way” (p. 109) and finally ended as American ambitions “changed from territorial expansion to economic intervention into Mexico” (p.110) in the later part of the 19th Century.

Fifteen‭ ‬years ago I became suddenly and unexpectedly disabled by an illness I never knew existed. 

 I was a nurse at the time. I had chosen my profession out of a deeply entrenched need for the safety and security I didn't have as a child. ‭"‬You'll always be able to find work‭; ‬people will always get sick.‭" ‬was the mantra I heard over and over as I reached adolescence and beyond. So--‭ ‬even though my dream was to be a scientist or a journalist-preferably a little of both,‭ ‬I chose nursing. 

Nevertheless,‭ ‬there I was:‭ ‬46‭ ‬years old and single,‭ ‬no money in the bank to speak of and unable to work. To this day I am disabled,‭ ‬and after‭ ‬15‭ ‬years of living on Social Security Disability,‭ ‬I have literally nothing left that I can call‭ "‬mine.‭" ‬I get by,‭ ‬but every day is a struggle and an assault on my security,‭ ‬safety and self-esteem. Nothing in my life is certain anymore,‭ ‬yet,‭ ‬there is one thing that I know to be true. I could not have gotten by for all these years were it not for the help of my family and a few good friends,‭ ‬no matter how strong I was. And believe me,‭ ‬when real disaster strikes,‭ ‬you do not feel very strong at all. 

My point is that there will always be emergencies in life-big and small.  There are no guarantees and no matter how well one prepares,‭ ‬some things are just too big to overcome on your own. 

I agree wholeheartedly that we in the U.S. need to stop putting all of our eggs in big government's‭ "‬basket‭"; ‬Lord knows it is moldy‭ ‬and falling apart,‭ ‬anyway. Yet I would much rather see Americans learning to trust one another again‭–‬learning to help each other and to ask for help,‭ ‬rather‭ ‬than have each of us individually clambering out to the backyard to build fallout shelters. 

The Conservatives in the US talk about the‭ "‬rugged individualism‭" ‬that built this country‭; ‬but in truth,‭ ‬what kept our forefathers going in hard times wasn't rugged individualism,‭ ‬it was compassion,‭ ‬mutual respect and the sharing of resources. The pioneers who crossed the Rockies in wagon trains didn't make it to the coast by going it alone. 


So,‭ ‬by all means,‭ ‬be prepared. I am. I have a disaster kit‭; ‬first‭ ‬aid supplies,‭ ‬water purifying tablets and plastic sheeting and duct tape for the windows in the event of a biological attack. I have several flashlights and all sorts of batteries,‭ ‬lots and lots of candles and waterproof matches and canned goods,‭ ‬too. If‭ ‬you have the land and the resources for a small farm and the ability to can or preserve your own food-do it. It's a great idea,‭ ‬as is a wood stove,‭ ‬as long as you do not live in an apartment. 

But while you are at it,‭ ‬get to know your neighbors.

Sometime in the fifth or sixth century BCE, a prince who would one day be called Buddha was born. Over the course of his life, he renounced the world and became enlightened, and his teachings led to the formation of Buddhism—the most orthodox sect of which is known as Theravada Buddhism. The religion is around twenty five hundred years old; it looks different today than it did when Buddha was alive. This can be seen all over, for instance in the Theravada nation of Sri Lanka, where the annual water-cutting ceremony is observed. Monks and laymen alike participate in this ceremony, and it holds some religious significance, despite Buddha never teaching about any festivity of the sort. These differences run all the way from the superficial traditions to the soteriological core of the religion. The Theravada Buddhist community, both from the monastic perspective and from the lay perspective, has had to change its doctrinal principles over time. This can be attributed to forces both external and internal, both hostile and benign.
	There are a number of qualifying terms this discussion will make frequent use of. There is the concept of internal versus external. Here, an internal force is defined as a force borne of members of the Buddhasasana, regardless of monastic status. An external force is any force from non-Buddhists. A hostile force is any force that damages or intends to damage the Buddhist community—a force borne of a negative perception of Buddhism. A benign force is a force that does not wish to harm or help the Buddhist community—though it may end up doing one or the other as a byproduct. These terms will come up repeatedly throughout this discussion.
	First, it is important to investigate the basics of the religion—the doctrines that lie at the core of Theravada Buddhism. Buddhists seek refuge in the triple gem of the Buddha, the Dhamma, and the Sangha. The Dhamma is essentially comprised of the Tripitaka—the three baskets—of Buddhist text. The Sutta Pitaka contains all the Suttas, the Vinaya Pitaka contains the disciplinary rules, and the Abhidhamma Pitaka contains the metaphysical components of Buddhism. The metaphysical notions consist of things like Anatta—no soul, Dukkha—inherent suffering in life, and Anicca—impermanence of everything. Only by recognizing these concepts can one end Sansara, the cycle of death and rebirth, which happens continuously. Along with Sansara will end lobha—desire, dosa—hatred, and moha—delusion, when one becomes enlightened. In the Vinaya Pitaka, rules for life are set forth. For laymen, there are five precepts (I shall not kill, I shall not lie, I shall not steal, I shall not misbehave sexually, and I shall not take intoxicating substances). For monks, there are many more disciplinary rules to be followed. The most fundamental doctrinal notion in Buddhism is the notion of the four noble truths. First, Dukkha; the truth that life is suffering. Second, that attachment causes suffering. Third, that suffering can be overcome.

In my quest to become a social worker, I aim to focus on the Division of Family and Children Services. My goal is to support children who have been abused or neglected and offer assistance to troubled families. The values I bring to the social work field are service, respect, ethical conduct, a commitment to strengthening relationships among individuals, and a dedication to continuous professional growth to stay competent in my field. These values are not just essential for social workers but are deeply ingrained in my personal beliefs.

Ever since high school and college, I've desired to help others, but I lacked clarity on the best career path. Witnessing many people turn away from their problems in denial and using subpar coping mechanisms further fueled my resolve. This observation led me to pursue a Bachelor’s degree in Psychology. Post-graduation from Piedmont College in 2009, I took a hiatus to explore my options. One summer, I visited a friend who introduced me to a sixteen-year-old boy sitting anxiously on her couch. He was there to escape his abusive parents. The next day, I learned he had contacted the police. Eager to assist, I drove to his parents' house. I approached the police with my recent degree in Psychology. The police asked me to speak with the parents, as they saw nothing they could legally do for the boy. During the conversation, the parents appeared nervous and blamed their son’s "manipulative" behavior for involving outsiders in "simple" disputes. This experience sparked my interest in a career in social work to help families resolve such issues.

An additional crucial value in social work is social justice. Our society claims to value the individual but often follows archaic traditions that stifle true uniqueness. If we mourn lost individuals, why do we strive to conform to everyone else? I embrace my individuality and reject limiting myself to fit societal norms. Throughout high school and college, I protested social injustices by expressing myself through unorthodox hair colors, clothing, and piercings, declaring my involvement with GSBA, and fighting against racism and discrimination. I advocate for social justice and will persist in challenging injustices.

The following paper delves into the Biological and Sociocultural models of insomnia. The Biological model explores genetic and medical aspects, while the Sociocultural model examines environmental factors and their links to race, ethnicity, demographics, and socioeconomic status. The review of insomnia via these models provides insight into various research studies and their findings, critiquing their strengths and weaknesses.

Insomnia can manifest as a primary sleep disorder, a secondary sleep disorder related to mental health issues, or a sleep disorder due to other medical complications or substance intake. Primary sleep disorders are classified into Dyssomnias or Parasomnias. Dyssomnias include Primary Insomnia (difficulty falling or staying asleep) and Primary Hypersomnia (difficulty staying awake), while Parasomnias involve behavioral or physiological sleep disturbances such as Nightmare Disorder and Sleepwalking Disorder. Insomnia related to other mental disorders is linked to Axis I (Clinical Disorders) or Axis II (Personality Disorders or Mental Retardation).

The Biological model of sleep disorders emphasizes genetic factors and physiological aspects. Orexin neurons in the hypothalamus regulate sleep and wakefulness. A study on mice found that GABAB receptors on these neurons modulate sleep/wake cycles. When GABAB receptors are activated, sleep is promoted. When inhibited, anxiety is reduced and sleep is induced. Baclofen, a GABAB agonist, increased sleep time in the study (Matsuki et al., 2009). This suggests that the findings in mice can translate to humans, indicating a genetic and environmental basis for sleep disorders. However, this model has limitations. It may not account for all cases of insomnia, and individual variations in genetic makeup can affect sleep quality. The Sociocultural implications suggest that inherited phenotypes could impact sleep regulation, and receptor alterations could naturally disturb sleep, affecting daily life.

This paper focuses on three aspects of Central Auditory Processing Disorder (CAPD). First, it provides a brief definition of the disorder. Next, it explains diagnosis, highlighting common signs, or "red flags". Finally, it offers ways teachers in a mainstream classroom setting can support a student with CAPD.

CAPD, or Auditory Processing Disorder (APD), "refers to how efficiently and effectively the central nervous system (CNS) processes auditory information. Specifically, it involves how the brain interprets what we hear, particularly distinguishing words from background noise" (American Speech-Language-Hearing Association, 2005). Individuals with CAPD can hear normally but have difficulty processing auditory information, making it a condition distinct from "hearing impaired".

The first documented mention of the disorder dates to the mid-1950s, initially called "auditory imperception" (American Speech-Language-Hearing Association, 2005). Italian researchers Bocca, Calearo, and Cassinari began developing tests for children with communication disorders in 1954, and Kimura introduced dichotic testing in 1961, creating a model to explain how the brain processes auditory information. A national conference in 1977 further stimulated research on CAPD.

CAPD can manifest in various ways: difficulty locating sounds, distinguishing between sounds, recognizing sound patterns, detecting changes in speech, being affected by subsequent sounds, interpreting sound clues, and understanding the sequence of auditory information (Ferre).

Diagnosis involves screening through systematic observation and tests of auditory function, conducted by audiologists, speech-language pathologists, psychologists, or others. There is no definitive diagnostic tool or known cause for CAPD. Tests often present patients with multiple simultaneous auditory stimuli and ask them to differentiate specific items, while advanced tests may involve recording acoustic signals within the ear and measuring responses.

Twelfth Night seems to suggest that while disguise can indeed be useful for long-term deception, it is crucial to eventually shed this new identity, or risk losing one's true self. A primary issue when ending a deception, however, is the potential for alienation. Thus, one must weigh the importance of self-preservation against the preservation of relationships. While some may react neutrally to discovering a deception, others may be deeply offended, especially when it comes to gender role reversals.

Viola, for instance, feels compelled to disguise herself as a man to protect herself in a foreign land. While this strategy initially works, it also distances her from the female support network she needs. It doesn't help that her disguise is so convincing that Olivia mistakes her for Sebastian and falls in love with her. “Whither, my lord? Cesario, husband, stay.” (5.1.138) Furthermore, Viola must handle romantic feelings towards Orsino and the confusion of Olivia's affections: “Boy, thou hast said to me a thousand times/ Thou never shouldst love woman like to me.” (5.1.260-261)

Though this may seem progressive, modern viewers might interpret Twelfth Night as showing how deception can help bring suppressed emotions to the forefront, particularly in Olivia and Orsino's cases. Certain passages may hint at unexpressed feelings that Cesario/Viola’s appearance forces them to confront. For example, is Olivia drawn to Cesario because of his perceived masculinity, or does she secretly harbor feelings for women? One could argue that Olivia is more likely to be parodied as someone who judges others solely based on appearances. This is evident in her swift shift from Cesario to Sebastian and her newfound familial affection towards Cesario/Viola: “A sister, you are she.” (5.1.315)

German colonial rule was renowned for its harshness, especially in relation to the Ovaherero and Nama genocide in German South West Africa. However, it's crucial to note that the German colonial empire was not uniform in its policies or ruling methods, varying greatly by region. Educational offerings across the colonies were similarly diverse. Upon taking control of German East Africa (now Tanganyika) in 1919, the British found a populace that was largely educated and literate. German educational initiatives in Kamerun and other colonies were even commended by contemporary writers.

In stark contrast, South West Africa (present-day Namibia) had a very different experience. Unlike East Africa, where the government actively engaged in educating natives through state schools, the task of educating locals in South West Africa was primarily left to missionary societies with minimal government support. The colony did see considerable investment in European education, with robust government funding for state schools and missionary institutions. These educational policies had lasting impacts on South West Africa, long after the end of German rule. While other German colonies boasted significant numbers of literate and educated Africans, in South West Africa, the majority remained untouched, uneducated, and illiterate. Various social, political, and economic factors contributed to this disparity. This paper aims to explore these factors, particularly examining new research on the attitudes of settlers and colonial authorities towards native Africans.

There is a rich body of literature on education within the German colonial empire. Most of these sources are in German and were penned in the early twentieth century, either during or soon after the colonial period. Early works primarily described the educational systems of these colonies. Later English-language works expanded upon this discourse through comparative studies and detailed analyses of specific educational aspects. These studies highlighted significant differences in the educational systems of various colonies. One of the most notable works to tackle the paper's topic is Cohen's study on education in South West Africa and East Africa. Cohen compares the educational systems of these two colonies and discusses the factors responsible for their differences. According to Cohen, the substantial settler population in South West Africa accounted for many of its educational system's distinctive features.

South West Africa's climate was relatively temperate, although much of the territory is arid desert. This hospitable climate attracted a European population that grew to nearly 15,000 by 1913, compared to East Africa's next largest settler population of 5,336.

The classification of Popular Music has expanded significantly over the past 100 years, encompassing countless genres and sub-genres that it's challenging to list them all. Most, if not all, genres—rap, rock, country, jazz, folk, to name a few—have brought forth numerous sub and sub-sub genres within their scope. Notably, the sub-genre of Heavy Metal rock has become one of the most expressive and diverse genres of popular music in the last 40 years. Its expressiveness lies in its wide range of emotions, tending toward the darker side of the spectrum. It's diverse because people soon recognized its flexibility and began to create their own sub-genres, which spawned further sub-sub-genres, continuing to this day.

Today, the heavy metal movement is so fragmented that it's hard to pinpoint what exactly constitutes heavy metal. It has absorbed themes from various other genres but originated from somewhere. To grasp the metal music prevalent today, one must first understand the essence of the metal movement and why it's a movement rather than just a genre.

Metal is, in many ways, a movement defined by darkness. It can be seen as a "music of more"—more bass, more volume, more violence, more theatricality. Less primitivism, more skill; metal bands truly know their instruments and it's evident in their music. Metal is also heavily drug-influenced. A psychedelic drug boom in the mid-70s led to people creating crazy, other-worldly records, using drugs as an outlet for their creativity. It possesses dark, visceral qualities, which was novel to the music scene as a lot of popular music didn't delve into the darker emotional spectrum. Later generations of metal also drew influence from the dark qualities of the Romantic Era. Lyrics like the following exemplify the darkness inherent in the movement:

**Byrne**

These lyrics from Helter Skelter display the darker side of the Beatles. The song's up and down rhythm is interpreted as a reflection of drug use. It's considered one of the first Heavy Metal songs as a response to a Rolling Stones song of a heavier, darker nature. The Beatles aimed to show they could be as heavy as the Stones, so they included it on The White Album.

A few decades before the Surrealists started crafting their surreal dream worlds through paint, Henri Rousseau was busy crafting his own dreams, both literally and metaphorically. The Dream, a 1910 masterpiece by the renowned Post-Impressionist, is more than just a depiction of a woman in awe amidst a dream landscape. It embodies Rousseau’s personal dreams and goals as an artist. Since he began his artistic journey, he yearned for recognition, acceptance, and praise from fellow artists and art enthusiasts. However, Rousseau found himself grappling with a significant internal conflict: to either conform to established styles to gain acceptance or to maintain his creative independence and uniqueness.

To fully appreciate The Dream from this perspective, one must first delve into Rousseau’s life story. Born on May 21, 1844, in Laval, France, Rousseau grew up in a family with a tinsmith and hardware dealer father who enjoyed bourgeois prosperity. He lacked formal art training and worked as a gabelou, an employee of the municipal toll service, until he was 40, often mistakenly referred to as a douanier, a customs inspector. The loss of his first wife, Clémence, and eight infant children left him with only one child, Julia, and profound grief. Painting became his refuge, offering him comfort and new beginnings. Unlike contemporaries who idealized peasants in their art, Rousseau was a folk painter, representing the hopes and dreams of the common people.

Rousseau’s desire for art world acceptance becomes clearer when considering his circumstances: he was untrained in formal painting, started late in life, and was painting alongside better-known and more talented artists. He didn’t gain recognition until around the same time as Matisse started building his reputation. According to Jan Gordon’s Modern French Painters, while both artists were competitors, they differed in style, subject matter, and motivations. Matisse feared painting in a clichéd way, while Rousseau aspired to create such conventional art that he would be accepted into the Artiste Français.

Many a wise thinker has pondered the deep connection between ethics and aesthetics, truth and beauty. I maintain that there's a fundamental reason for this. As John Keats put it in his "Ode on a Grecian Urn", "Beauty is truth, truth beauty—/ That is all ye know on earth, and all ye need to know." Much of what we learn about ethics and aesthetics comes from education or personal experience. However, we seem to appreciate these concepts without being explicitly taught them. Both ethics and aesthetics are about describing rather than prescribing. Our explorations into morality and beauty aim to explain what makes a piece of art or a deed moral or beautiful, rather than dictating rules for creating good art or moral behavior.

Criticizing art or morals often fails to capture their essence completely. For example, a discussion about the merit of da Vinci's Mona Lisa might touch on elements like foreground, background, contrast, or cultural context, but it won't fully elucidate why it's considered great art. Instead, when asked about a favorite work of art or literature, it's usual to hear phrases like "There's just something about it" followed by a more complex explanation. I believe both art and morals can't be fully reduced to a description of their qualities. Flannery O'Connor put it well: "A story is a way to say something that can't be said in any other way...you tell a story because a statement would be inadequate." Similarly, no matter how meticulously we describe a literary work's qualities, there's still something transcendent that remains. Ethics shares this same property. Wittgenstein said, "It is clear that ethics cannot be expressed. Ethics is transcendental." This "something," this intangible essence, is what makes art and morality powerful and connects them.

I believe ethics and art are so closely related because we experience them most profoundly on a noumenal level, as Kant would put it. They affect us at a depth that can be experienced but not fully explained. This connection is especially strong in literature. As McKean notes, "What most distinguishes literature from the other arts, what is, in truth, unique about the art, is its moral quality. It may be that moral standards are inappropriate to other arts, like music, for instance, but they seem to be as relevant to literature as they are to life itself. Living necessarily involves values...Literature is important to us precisely because of the values we find there."

Today's Germany is a mighty force, a united nation with a distinct culture that echoes through the shadows of the Alps in München and down to the Baltic Sea in Kiel. This unique culture can be felt from Köln along the Rhine River, through the heart of Germany, to the Saxon city of Dresden by the Elbe. Given this rich tapestry of culture, it's no surprise that Germany, as it stands today, is a fusion of various origins and tribes.

The ancestral home of the Germans is Germania. The etymology of the name is a topic of scholarly debate. Tacitus suggested the name came from the Tungrian tribe, who were previously known as Germans before crossing the Rhine to clash with Gaulish forces. Julius Caesar first used the term "Germanus" in his commentary on the Gallic Wars, where he fought the Gauls and battled Germanic tribes who frequently crossed the Rhine. He adopted the term from the Gauls themselves to differentiate between conquered and unconquered peoples. Some believe the name originates from the German spear, known as a ger, or from the Old Irish word garim meaning "to shout," indicating the Germans' loud nature. (Tacitus, 98; Julius Caesar, 50-40 BC; Names of Germany)

The early Roman historian Tacitus, in his AD 98 work "De Origine et situ Germanorum," noted that he considered the Germans aboriginal, having no mixed origins. He suggested that they came by sea rather than land, as who would leave Asia or Africa for Italy to settle in Germany with its harsh climate and rugged demeanor? (Tacitus, 98)

Who would willingly relocate from Rome to Germania? Certainly not the Romans, at least not initially. They would send forth their conquests into the lands of Germania for resources and lead occasional campaigns, but ultimately, they would return to their vast empire. Thus, as Germanic tribes began appearing in the mid-first century, they lived on the empire's borders, trading goods and offering their skills in the Roman army. (Ozment, 2005, pg. 17)

I gazed down at the scene before me, my mind a blank slate, stunned by the sheer volume of detail. Silently, almost mechanically, my consciousness parsed the image, refusing to attach any meaning to it. Thoughts flickered in and out of my awareness, smooth and fluid, as if I was merely an observer to the events unfolding. Once, I had purchased an art instruction book called "The New Drawing on the Right Side of the Brain," hoping to learn how to draw ever since I was six years old. It taught me to frame any image, turning a complex scene into a simple one. Staring at the bowl of fruit before me, I was overwhelmed, unable to mentally impose the artist’s frame. The room felt like the beginning of a masterpiece, the start of a story titled "Work in Brown."

My hand reached for my tool of choice, muscles tensing and relaxing as I moved. Water swirled, crystal clear and unruffled. A few flakes broke away, vanishing into nothingness. My hand struck the toilet handle, muscles taut and anxious. The offending package remained stuck, like a slug on the bottom of the toilet. I held the mop loosely, feet wide for balance, a tie awkwardly around my neck, and frowned at the mess. A few more flushes, more moments of quiet reflection, then I reached for the toilet paper roll, wrapping it around my hand like an oven mitt. Standing tall, I dipped my hand into the bowl, like a mother retrieving a Thanksgiving turkey from the oven.

Teenagers are perishing behind the wheel, and this grim trend has various factors at its core. The National Institutes of Health note that the teen brain is not yet equipped to handle the dangers of driving. The lack of experience turns out to be a significant issue, leading to more fatal crashes, vehicle rollovers, speeding, and road departures.

When teens travel with peers—something that happens frequently—the likelihood of accidents rises even more. A study by the Southern California Injury Prevention Research Center found a direct link between the age of passengers and the number of accidents.

Several states have implemented provisional licenses to curb teen driving risks, limiting driving hours and banning other minors as passengers. However, psychologist Marvin Zuckerman believes even 18 is too young for a regular license. Research indicates that teens under 19-20 crave risks for the thrill, making it crucial to delay driving until this tendency wanes. Issuing licenses to young teens will likely increase fatal accidents and may lead to an alarming death toll in the coming years, especially with the Baby Boomers' children soon eligible to drive.

Legislative solutions could be simple and effective. Schools could offer driver's education classes, but no one under 18 should be allowed to drive. A provisional permit could still be issued with practical training hours required, based on current state requirements. Since teen driving deaths span all states, nationwide legislation would be a reasonable and effective way to protect teens everywhere.

The proposed legislation isn't groundbreaking but is a practical step towards addressing a serious issue.

I snooped around the Library of Congress's collection of old Edison films and chanced upon fifteen trick films from 1895 to 1901. These early films are known for their clever use of editing to create optical illusions. My research mainly delved into the descriptive poetics of the trick films and the unique characteristics of a few later ones. Most of these films are stage-bound, composed from a frontal proscenium, with no camera movement, and stick to long and medium shots, adhering to the rule that one shot equals one film. However, some films from the early 20th century dared to break these rules by incorporating multiple shots.

One common trait among these trick films is their filming within an interior set, captured from a fixed frontal proscenium. The camera doesn't budge from its position to follow figures or objects, mimicking the theatre and vaudeville traditions from which they originated. This static camera setup often leads to actors moving side-to-side, never towards or away from the camera, as seen in Uncle Josh in a Spooky Hotel (1900), where actors enter from the right and move horizontally. Even when figures leave the frame, the camera doesn't follow.

The frontal proscenium style also means that shots are typically long and medium shots, with close-ups being absent. This is directly rooted in the theatre and vaudeville practices, where the audience sees the entire performance at once, framed by the stage's borders. Actors rarely move from the center toward the camera, so close-ups are a no-show.

Generally, early trick films stick to one conceptual shot per film, restricting their length to about a minute or less, depending on frames per second. This limits their dramatic or narrative use to short vaudeville-style tricks like magic, disappearing acts, and quick switches, with minimal story. While a viewer might see one conceptual shot, this doesn't equate to one physical shot. A single "shot" can be composed of several joined segments to create illusions of apparition or disappearance. For instance, in The Execution of Mary, Queen of Scots (1895), a careful look reveals the start of the shot with Mary's severed "head," despite the film being conceptually one shot in the viewer's eye.

John Taylor of Caroline was an early and passionate advocate for Republicanism. He primarily worked as an agriculturalist, and his brief stint in politics made him known for his unwavering stance on personal freedoms and government. Taylor believed in the superiority of agrarian work, which shaped his views on sovereignty, the Constitution, and even the judicial system.

Taylor saw the United States as an opportunity to establish an ideal system, as there were no established traditions to impede its creation. He strongly upheld the natural rights of man, believing they were interconnected. He argued that if one right was denied, others would fail, and the value of those remaining would diminish. These rights should be beyond government reach. He also believed that the "state of nature" allowed the powerful to prosper, but in society, this should not be the case.

To create this ideal society, Taylor thought a government must acknowledge the inherent good and evil in man. He was firm in his belief in a dualistic morality, stating, "As government is exercised by man, all its virtues and vices must be human" (Ibid., pg. 167). He considered good principles those that protect private property, improve agriculture, and discourage capitalism. A government founded on these principles would function equitably despite its leaders' avarice and self-interest. He believed self-interest was a natural trait of man, but only became evil when it led to sub-societies exploiting others. A good government was needed to keep man's natural evil in check, and it must be closely watched to prevent corrupt principles.

Like many Republicans of his time, Taylor advocated for a strict construction of the Constitution. He wanted a Federal government with limited powers, no more than explicitly stated. He knew an extensive Federal government was likely to be tyrannical, but a simple literal interpretation could also be dangerous without considering the writers' intent. He viewed the Declaration of Independence as the true charter of the United States, describing it as a group of sovereign states rather than one nation.

Checking back on Figure 17, there was a sharp decrease in commuter log entries in the third month of the project. This was quite concerning, and the reason behind it remains unclear. With the arrival of winter on a New England campus, there's a natural drop in commuters traveling by bicycle or on foot, which likely accounts for part of the decline. December also marks the end of the fall semester, when everyone is focused on finishing assignments, processing grades, and more. Submitting the commuter log might have slipped their minds amidst all this. Additionally, December brings the start of the busy holiday season and a month-long break for students and faculty, during which many don't need to visit campus. Classes resume for the spring semester in late January, which could also reflect the low number of logs for that month. However, this doesn't explain the low number for February. It's possible that any project like this experiences an initial surge of enthusiasm, which naturally wanes. To combat this, we introduced the Carpool Challenge Week in March, a special campaign to boost the initiative, which did lead to an increase in log submissions for that month. The project faced two main challenges: the natural decrease in engagement and the breaks during the holiday and semester seasons. Another challenge is that many people enjoy the freedom and flexibility of driving their cars, which is deeply ingrained in our culture. Thus, providing incentives for alternative commuting is crucial. We offered gift certificates to local eateries, coffee shops, massage therapists, the local bookstore, and even some national chains. It would have been interesting to see if larger prizes like bicycles, hybrid cars, or electric cars could have increased participation. The nature of the prizes remained consistent throughout the project. If the prizes had increased in value over time, such as adding a bicycle in December and a hybrid or electric car in January, engagement might have stayed high instead of declining.

An ETF, or exchange traded fund, is similar to an index fund but trades on an exchange like a stock. It offers the diversification of an index fund and the benefits of individual stock ownership, like short selling and margin buying. Plus, you can buy as little as one share in any transaction. ETFs have lower expense ratios than average mutual funds, but they come with a trade cost, like buying a stock. There's a wide variety of ETFs to choose from, but it's crucial to assess whether the stated benefits, such as diversification, are actually present and to what extent. We'll explore the ETF IHF and compare it against its top 10 holdings to see if owning a single ETF is better than owning a diversified portfolio of the ten stocks, and to check if there are better stock configurations that could yield a more optimal Sharpe ratio or return.

To simplify our evaluation, we'll consider only the top 10 holdings, which make up 63.58% of the ETF's assets. Below are the top 10 holdings and their respective percentages of total assets.

To estimate how well these ten stocks represent the ETF IHF, we can use their current % of assets, normalized to 100%, to calculate the contributions of each stock to a portfolio's Beta and Return if the portfolio was made of these 10 stocks in the proportion the ETF holds. The calculations of Beta and return are shown below:

From the chart, it's clear that a portfolio of just the top 10 holdings could offer a 6.11% higher return and a 0.12 lower Beta than the ETF. However, these two portfolios might not be statistically different from each other.

To determine if these portfolios are statistically different, we'll calculate the standard deviation of each of the top 10 stocks and normalize it to 100% to compare their accumulated standard deviation to that of the ETF IHF.

Dream-land is one of Edgar Allan Poe's self-proclaimed better poems. In “Dream-Land,” he uses the term “Thulé” in lines 6 and 56, which Mabbott traces back to Virgil. Virgil used the term to refer to an island north of Britain, considered the edge of the known world by the Greeks. While Virgil certainly used the term, there's a more current source to which some credit must be given. Poe was particularly fascinated by German authors. Karl J. Arndt, in his book Poe’s Politian and Goethe’s Mignon, points out the similarity between Poe’s and Goethe’s poems, concluding that Poe was indeed imitating Goethe.

The Oxford Companion to English Literature notes that Goethe was a renowned writer of the poetic drama Faust, published in two parts, with the first appearing in 1808 and the second in the year of Goethe's death, 1832. Within the second part of Faust, there's a short poem titled “The King of Thulé.” This poem tells of a king whose wife dies after giving him a goblet. He then begins to drink heavily and mourn his loss, ultimately deciding to end his life by throwing the goblet into the ocean. The description of this king and the atmosphere in “Dream-Land” are very similar, perhaps reflective of Poe’s own struggles with loss and alcohol. Faust was also adapted into a romantic drama by H P Grattan in 1842, just a year before Poe used the term Thule in “The Pit and the Pendulum.”

Poe references Thule twice in his collected writings. He uses the phrase “ultma Thule” in “The Pit and the Pendulum,” and in “Dream-Land,” he uses the term twice to frame the poem. “The King of Thulé” and “Dream-Land” can be seen as companion pieces. In “Dream-Land,” the speaker describes the bleak landscape of Thule, filled with the ghostly memories of dead friends and a world devoid of color. This description resonates with the themes in “The King of Thulé,” where the king has lost his will to live and is haunted by his wife's memory. The poem reads as if the speaker has stepped into Goethe’s work.

Goethe was a significant author that Poe would have known, if for no other reason than his respect for Tennyson. When asked if he admired Tennyson, Poe did mention his appreciation for Tennyson, but he would also have been exposed to Goethe’s work through various reproductions that became popular after the original publication.

In California, a customer injured after slipping and falling on an applesauce spill in a grocery store might be awarded punitive damages if the store manager's actions showed malice. The manager knew of the spill twice but didn't clean it for a half-hour because he was eating dinner. The manager's actions could be seen as willful and conscious disregard for probable harm, even if not intending to cause harm. A judge is unlikely to dismiss Jennifer Palmer's punitive damage claim if she can present evidence that the store manager's actions were malicious.

Four years ago, I attended a course on Islam at CBC. One of the main topics that sparked heated debate was whether Islam is a hostile religion. This question is even more pertinent today. Reflecting on the events since 9/11, I've noticed a shift in mass media's portrayal of Islam and extremists, from hostility to extreme tolerance. In 2001, a presidential candidate with the name Barack Obama, who has a Muslim background in his family, was unimaginable.

The life of the Prophet Muhammad, as recounted in his biography, is intriguing. The narrative paints Muhammad as a sort of martyr, misunderstood and humble, rather than someone who forcibly converted tribes. According to the biography, one by one, people came to see the 'truth' in his teachings and sought him out. This style of portrayal is reminiscent of Jesus' ministry, particularly the miracle of multiplying food—mutton and milk—to feed forty men. This approach seems to downplay the life and miracles of Jesus.

Moreover, many stories in the biography aim to provide 'proof' of conversions to Islam, often presented as third-party accounts. While this might seem to validate the stories, it also makes them appear more questionable. What bothers me most is the attempt to elevate Muhammad to a godly figure, portraying him as humble, wise, and gentle. However, historical accounts contradict this image, and I can't help but wonder if Muslims today are aware of the true history behind Muhammad's rise to power.

The teachings of Jesus and the beliefs he held during his lifetime were swiftly abandoned in the evolution of Christian thought that followed his life. A historical trend shows Christianity drifting further away from its origin over time. Today's world displays increasing awareness and unprecedented progressive tendencies. While some people cling to traditional beliefs and resist any thinking beyond what they were taught, this group's influence may not be significant enough to shape the whole. Among Christians, a growing historical awareness will intensify in future years. There will be a growing desire to distinguish between the doctrines added to Christianity over time and the original intent of the religion's founder. It may take decades or even centuries, but the outcome is inevitable: a reversal in the trend of Christian history. This will involve a progression back to its original form, with a movement gaining strength that peels away layers of doctrine, one by one, as if turning back the clock. This reversal will lead to a clearer understanding of Jesus' teachings, before any other ideas were introduced. When this trend sweeps through the United States and Europe, influencing millions to worship as if living in Jesus' time, the church will remain strong to guide the way. However, with the theological clock turned back, the extreme diversity in Christendom will reduce to more uniformity. Between regions, denominations, and divisions of every kind, differences will give way to increasing similarities. Human history is filled with great reversals. Just consider how Christians were once persecuted, shunned, and killed by the Roman Empire, but later, the empire became a Christian institution. Our country has evolved from African-American slavery to African-American leadership. The great reversal coming in our future will play out in the realm of the Christian religion, undoing history to seek the source and reducing diversity in the process. It is important to note that part of what will make this process possible is reading Jesus' words metaphorically, rather than literally. So, what has changed since Jesus' lifetime?

If we look far back into history, we find only Judaism, the theological foundation for Christianity. Monotheism, the perception of a divinely revealed religion, and the authority of the Hebrew scriptures were already present by the time Rome took control of Jerusalem in 63 B.C.E. The Jewish population was not united; they divided into Sadducees, Pharisees, Essenes, Zealots, and a majority of ordinary people.

In my view, The Jungle vividly demonstrates humanity's inherent greed and self-interest. Individuals only focus on enhancing their own lives and ignore others, especially those less fortunate. Sinclair's narrative emphasizes this theme through the owners and managers of the colossal factories. These figures are singularly driven by the desire to expand and prosper their businesses, indifferent to the harm caused by their operations. "The line of the buildings stood clear-cut and black against the sky; here and there out of the mass rose the great chimneys, with the river of smoke streaming away to the end of the world" paints a stark picture of the pollution and damage inflicted by these factories. The owners carelessly disregard the plight of workers and the ecosystem, exemplified by the choking smoke and waste from the pens. They prioritize profit above all, even exploiting their employees' labor. "So from the top to bottom the place is simply a seething cauldron of jealousies and hatreds; there is no loyalty or decency anywhere about it, there is no place in it where a man counted for anything against a dollar," Sinclair writes, highlighting the harsh working conditions and lack of worker's safety regulations. This environment resulted in employees being treated as disposable, with no support or help even in death. Unions, meant to protect workers, often profited off these very individuals, exacerbating their suffering. Employees were trapped in a system where they were essentially slaves, forced to endure deplorable conditions both inside and outside the factories.

Many authors employ various methods to evoke specific feelings or attitudes in their readers towards significant topics. One such technique is the pairing of adjectives with nouns in an unconventional manner. Another method is the symbolism of objects, where a symbol is given a particular meaning and then utilized for the same purpose. F. Scott Fitzgerald uses these techniques extensively in his novel "The Great Gatsby." For instance, he often associates colors like yellow, green, white/gray, and red/pink with certain emotions or themes. In "The Great Gatsby," Fitzgerald builds up a symbolic meaning for white/gray and later uses this meaning to convey a sense of uniformity or insignificance around particular subjects.

Fitzgerald establishes the meaning of white/gray in the novel's beginning, where he frequently uses both colors. Characters like Daisy and Jordan are often "in white" (8), and even Nick wears "white flannels" (41) to Gatsby's party. The only instances where characters are not wearing white are during Nick's descriptions of Gatsby's party, where "the halls... are gaudy with primary colors" (40). Fitzgerald also employs white/gray to symbolize uniformity in people and places. For example, as Nick goes to work, he travels "down the white chasms of lower New York" (56), and the names of partygoers are "gray names" (61) on his timetable. Moreover, the novel describes simple or unimportant characters and places in terms of white/gray; Jordan and Daisy share a "white girlhood" (19), there are "gray cars" and "gray land" (23) in the valley of ashes, and an "Italian child" is described as "gray" (26) while a dog-seller is a "gray old man" (27).

After imbuing white/gray with a specific meaning, Fitzgerald uses these colors to represent uniformity or insignificance. This technique starts with Daisy, who is first depicted in a "white" dress in a "little white roadster." After a period without significant use of white or gray, Daisy's role becomes more uniform, like something Gatsby wants but cannot possess. Fitzgerald continues this pattern with Daisy wearing a "white" dress (115) and having a "gray haze of Daisy’s fur collar" (18) to emphasize her status as a uniform addition rather than a unique character.

San Diego County is a hotbed of agricultural activity, thanks to its mild, sunny climate. Crops grown here include tomatoes, citrus fruits, leafy greens, squash, broccoli, herbs, tree fruits like peaches and lemons, berries, honey, and peppers. There's a thriving market for organic community-supported agriculture, with many local organizations boasting lengthy waiting lists. Organic eggs and milk are also in high demand. Many organic farms offer tours and recreational activities like hiking and birdwatching. This type of operation allows farmers to benefit from government programs while enhancing habitat and offering educational experiences. However, organic farming can be more labor-intensive and costly due to the lack of chemical pesticides and fertilizers, and it may have higher pest and weed management costs. It often requires more labor and management to maintain soil health and biodiversity. Additionally, non-farming tasks such as planting cover crops, strategic grazing, and invasive species removal can also incur significant labor costs. This makes it a good idea for the landowner to seek financial aid or expertise to balance profits and habitat quality.

The selected land is a 160-acre parcel adjacent to the town of Potrero in unincorporated San Diego County, California. It's a mix of chaparral, nonnative Mediterranean grassland, and oak woodland near the Cleveland National Forest. This region is part of the East County Southern Foothills ecoregion of the San Diego Multiple Species Conservation Plan. The plan identifies over a hundred species of plants and animals, many of which are endangered or declining, such as the Stephens' kangaroo rat, mountain yellow-legged frog, various butterfly species, and the California gnatcatcher, while burrowing owls are also at risk. The land was inhabited by Native Americans for centuries and later used by cattle ranchers and cordwood sellers in the late 1800s. This parcel was part of an original homestead, likely used for grazing and/or wood production.

Culture shapes every negotiation, and it's not just about what it is, but also what it's not. It's not uniform, it's not singular, and it's not something you can judge or change. Saying "all Russians are stubborn" or "all Japanese are accommodating" is oversimplifying. Understanding culture's impact on negotiations is crucial. When exploring a foreign culture, we relate it to our own, and comparisons naturally arise. To understand a culture, study its history, prejudices, and values. Accept it, work within its boundaries, especially if you're at a disadvantage. Respecting traditions and beliefs helps overcome cultural barriers. Culture isn't just national; companies have their own culture too. In a negotiation, knowing your opponent's personal values can make all the difference. If saving face is valued, you won't publicly shame them. If a hard bargain is valued, don't rush to settle. Understanding these generalities before the table is crucial, but knowing your opponent personally can make the negotiation more effective.

“The fool hath said in his heart, ‘There is no God.’” This statement first appears in Psalm 14 of the Christian Bible and serves as the starting point for St. Anselm’s argument for the existence of God. Similarly, Thomas Aquinas also holds this belief. Given that both are arguing for the same idea, and our task is to determine which argument is stronger, we must assume, for the sake of simplicity, that both are correct in their belief in the God of the Bible. To compare their arguments effectively, we must focus on a God that matches the one they describe. Neither St. Anselm nor St. Thomas Aquinas offers a complete justification for belief in God.
	To demonstrate this, let’s first look at St. Anselm’s basic argument. Anselm’s approach involves gaining understanding through faith, suggesting that the proof for God lies within one’s own mind. He argues that since we can conceive of God’s existence, we cannot deny it. While his reasoning can be convoluted, the core of it is that the proof of God is found within our own understanding. This is a concept known as faith within Christian texts, where one accepts the existence of God without needing irrefutable empirical evidence.
	St. Thomas Aquinas, on the other hand, posits that the existence of God can be proven through reason and empirical evidence, without relying on faith. This approach could be advantageous for evangelism, as it allows new converts to be persuaded by logic alone. Aquinas presents five logical arguments supporting the existence of God: change, causation, contingency, degrees of excellence, and harmony. Each argument essentially shows that the proof of God lies in the logical necessity for his existence. For example, if you have a puzzle but one piece is missing, you can infer its features and existence based on the rest of the puzzle, even without seeing it.

Long ago, in the fifth or sixth century BCE, a future Buddha was born. Throughout his life, he left the world behind and achieved enlightenment, laying the foundation for Buddhism, with Theravada Buddhism being the most traditional sect. The faith has existed for around twenty-five hundred years, evolving significantly since Buddha's time. For example, in Sri Lanka, the annual water-cutting ceremony involves monks and laypeople, though Buddha never taught about such festivities. The Theravada Buddhist community has altered its core principles, influenced by both external and internal factors, both friendly and unfriendly. Let's delve into what makes Theravada Buddhism tick. Buddhists find solace in the triple gem: the Buddha, the Dhamma, and the Sangha. The Dhamma includes the Tripitaka, the three baskets, which contain Suttas, disciplinary rules, and metaphysical components. Key notions include Anatta (no soul), Dukkha (inherent suffering), and Anicca (impermanence). Understanding these concepts can help break the cycle of death and rebirth, known as Sansara, and eliminate lobha (desire), dosa (hatred), and moha (delusion). The Vinaya Pitaka outlines rules for life, with five precepts for laypeople and many more for monks. The core doctrine revolves around the four noble truths: first, life is suffering; second, attachment causes suffering; third, suffering can be overcome.

Once upon a time, the United States and Mexico were locked in a long-lasting rivalry that lasted from 1836 to 1893. The height of their animosity was the Mexican-American War of 1846-1848, where the U.S. triumphed over Mexico, securing Texas and the American Southwest. Other skirmishes occurred between them before the First World War. Their rivalry stemmed from disagreements on religion, culture, and tradition, as well as clashing material interests. This is not unusual for neighboring nations, as David M. Pletcher (1977) noted, “Only in Mexico and Cuba can one find long-lasting overarching American diplomatic problems” (p. 41). Both countries were geographically close to the U.S. and held rival positions, unlike many other Latin American nations that enjoyed good relations with the U.S. Religious differences, a remnant of colonial times, played a significant role in their enmity.

Sally Frahm (2001) highlighted that "if in the twentieth century Americans were opposed to fascism and communism, in the eighteenth and nineteenth they were opposed to Catholicism and monarchy" (p.86). Thus, the ideological struggle between the U.S. and Mexico was more about religion than politics, much like the Cold War between the U.S. and the Soviet Union. The distrust between them was passed down from their colonial rulers, the English and Spanish, blocking amiable foreign relations.

Diehl and Goerts (2000) documented 17 disputes between Mexico and the U.S. during their 57-year rivalry, most of which were territorial issues. Border raids and outlaw activities from American towns were major problems until both nations took military action on their borders (Schmitt 1974 p. 97).
